1
00:00:14,923 --> 00:00:19,255
<font color=#00FFFF><b>I WANTED WINGS</b></font>

2
00:00:35,584 --> 00:00:39,400
<font color=#00FFFF><b>Based on a Story by
ELEOANORE GRIFFIN and FRANK WEAD</b></font>

3
00:00:39,550 --> 00:00:42,452
<font color=#00FFFF><b>From the Book
I WANTED WINGS by
LIEUT. BEIRNE LAY. JR.</b></font>

4
00:01:04,300 --> 00:01:06,911
<font color=#00FFFF><b>This production was actally filmed
at Randolph Kelly and March Fields.</b></font>

5
00:01:07,583 --> 00:01:08,805
<font color=#00FFFF><b>The splendid colaboration of</b></font>

6
00:01:09,456 --> 00:01:12,030
<font color=#00FFFF><b> the Unied States Army Air Corps
is gratefully acknowledged.</b></font>

7
00:01:26,676 --> 00:01:30,100
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>BIRTHPLACE OF MANS WINGS, AMERICA
TODAY WATHES HER SKY WITH GRAVE CONCERN.</b></font>

8
00:01:30,680 --> 00:01:34,732
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>FOR IN THESE SKIES OF PEACE NATION IS
BUILDING THE UPPER BATTLEMENTS OF ITS DEFENSE. </b></font>

9
00:01:35,370 --> 00:01:37,935
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>TO THE OFFICERS AND MAN
OF THE UNITED STATES ARMY AIR CORPS</b></font>

10
00:01:38,506 --> 00:01:41,302
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>WHO CLIMB ON STRONG WINGS
TO MAN THESE HIGH RAMPARTS.</b></font>

11
00:01:42,092 --> 00:01:45,482
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>AND TO THE YOUNG MEN OF AMERICA
WHO WILL TAKE THEIR PLACES BESIDE THEM,</b></font>

12
00:01:45,896 --> 00:01:49,292
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>THIS MOTION
PICTURE IS DEDICATED.</b></font>

13
00:02:16,986 --> 00:02:18,740
This is Ranger Station 58.

14
00:02:18,948 --> 00:02:22,076
18 bombers.
Altitude estimated 15.000.

15
00:02:22,226 --> 00:02:25,454
Course southwest.
Now directly overhead.

16
00:02:40,449 --> 00:02:42,746
This is Mojave.
Yeah, Mojave.

17
00:02:42,771 --> 00:02:44,746
A big bunch of planes
are flying over here.

18
00:02:44,771 --> 00:02:48,012
They're going like San Hill
and headed for Los Angeles. Yeah.

19
00:02:48,179 --> 00:02:49,687
Okay.

20
00:03:09,547 --> 00:03:13,172
Anti aircraft companies.
Battery B. 52nd Monterrey.

21
00:03:13,197 --> 00:03:16,852
Duarte at command.
<i>27 heavy bombers passing over here.</i>

22
00:03:16,877 --> 00:03:18,978
<i>And estimated altitude 12.000.</i>

23
00:03:19,003 --> 00:03:21,306
<i>Changing course from south to east.</i>

24
00:03:23,345 --> 00:03:26,550
Warning net command to
Battery B. 52nd Monterrey.

25
00:03:26,575 --> 00:03:28,120
Message received. Okay.

26
00:03:28,699 --> 00:03:32,214
Wanting net command
23rd Pursuit Squadron. Go ahead.

27
00:03:32,239 --> 00:03:34,973
Warning net command to
Battery A. Morrow Bay.

28
00:03:34,998 --> 00:03:37,786
Repeat message, please.
Repeat message, please.

29
00:03:37,811 --> 00:03:40,606
<i>38th reconnaissance
to warning net command.</i>

30
00:03:40,631 --> 00:03:44,036
<i>Large enemy formation
just sighted over Palm Springs.</i>

31
00:03:44,061 --> 00:03:47,655
Southbound attackers estimated
over Santa Barbara in 12 minutes, sir.

32
00:03:47,680 --> 00:03:52,225
Headed directly for Los Angeles.
- That's my ground speed. 2-6-0.

33
00:03:54,046 --> 00:03:58,585
Transmit enemy positions in course to
all pursuit squadrons and antiaircraft units.

34
00:03:58,788 --> 00:04:02,056
Order 38. The reconnaissance
squadron maintain contact

35
00:04:02,411 --> 00:04:03,759
with enemy formation over Palm Springs.

36
00:04:04,099 --> 00:04:04,846
Blackout immediately.
- Yes, sir.

37
00:04:05,265 --> 00:04:08,743
Turn your boys loose with
their sirens, Chief. - Yes, sir.

38
00:04:12,668 --> 00:04:16,300
On the roof of the municipal building,
we're bringing you  an eye-witness account

39
00:04:16,324 --> 00:04:18,957
of the first simulated
air raid upon Los Angeles.

40
00:04:18,982 --> 00:04:21,840
Below us are the glittering
lights of a great city.

41
00:04:21,865 --> 00:04:24,887
At play and at peace.
Men and women are...

42
00:04:25,441 --> 00:04:28,600
There go the blackout sirens now.
Turn out your lights.  Pull down your blinds.

43
00:04:28,624 --> 00:04:30,272
Automobiles, please
switch off your headlights.

44
00:04:30,296 --> 00:04:33,257
Stand by your radios
for further instructions.

45
00:04:43,104 --> 00:04:45,416
Los Angeles is now rapidly blacking out.

46
00:04:54,915 --> 00:04:57,294
You there.
In the drugstore.

47
00:04:57,859 --> 00:04:59,857
Turn off that neon sign.

48
00:05:06,262 --> 00:05:08,129
Turn off your headlights, Mac.

49
00:05:15,582 --> 00:05:17,293
<i>35th Pursuit Squadron reporting.</i>

50
00:05:17,318 --> 00:05:19,941
<i>Successful interception
effective westbound formation.</i>

51
00:05:19,966 --> 00:05:23,277
We estimate all enemy units will
converge on Los Angeles in eight minutes.

52
00:05:23,732 --> 00:05:27,186
Order all remaining pursuit
squadrons up to intercept. - Yes, sir.

53
00:05:52,710 --> 00:05:55,917
The attacking bombers are reported
approaching the city from many directions.

54
00:05:55,918 --> 00:05:58,819
Parachute troops are
being dropped on the outskirts.

55
00:06:22,980 --> 00:06:26,447
Here come the bombers now.
You can probably hear them.

56
00:07:05,759 --> 00:07:07,089
There go the pursuit planes.

57
00:07:16,900 --> 00:07:18,119
Here comes the attack now.

58
00:07:18,299 --> 00:07:21,625
And believe you me, we can be
thankful the explosions are up there.

59
00:07:21,650 --> 00:07:23,235
And that they're not real bombs.

60
00:07:56,393 --> 00:07:59,565
The raid is over.
The lights blink on again.

61
00:07:59,590 --> 00:08:02,604
Once more of the city
takes up the tempo of normal life.

62
00:08:02,629 --> 00:08:04,762
No homes have been shattered.

63
00:08:04,787 --> 00:08:07,934
No fires sweep the gutted
streets of a murdered city.

64
00:08:07,959 --> 00:08:12,270
No terror or sorrow fills the
upturned lives of helpless civilians.

65
00:08:12,295 --> 00:08:14,309
For the United States is at peace.

66
00:08:14,334 --> 00:08:17,084
But these realistic maneuvers
are a convincing guarantee.

67
00:08:17,109 --> 00:08:20,638
That American soldiers and
citizens alike intend to be prepared.

68
00:08:20,663 --> 00:08:24,396
We return you now to our main studio.
One moment please. We have a bulletin here.

69
00:08:24,421 --> 00:08:27,430
An Army Flying Fortress bomber
en route back from maneuvers

70
00:08:27,455 --> 00:08:29,955
is reported to have crashed
in the desert. North of Marsh Field.

71
00:08:29,980 --> 00:08:33,257
And here is another bulletin.
The fate of the crew is not yet known.

72
00:08:33,282 --> 00:08:35,885
And officials refuse to
comment on the unconfirmed report

73
00:08:35,910 --> 00:08:38,896
that a woman was found
dead in the wrecked plane.

74
00:08:39,493 --> 00:08:40,829
Charge one.

75
00:08:40,854 --> 00:08:43,704
Violation of the 84th Article of War.

76
00:08:43,729 --> 00:08:45,049
Specification.

77
00:08:45,082 --> 00:08:47,925
In that Jefferson Young,
second lieutenant, Air Corps.

78
00:08:47,950 --> 00:08:51,222
Having received a lawful
command from Capt. Everett Mercer,

79
00:08:51,247 --> 00:08:53,980
Air Corps,
his superior officer,

80
00:08:54,005 --> 00:08:57,479
not to attempt to take off from
the scene of an emergency landing

81
00:08:57,504 --> 00:08:59,573
in a Flying Fortress airplane,

82
00:08:59,598 --> 00:09:02,089
did near Spring Canyon, California,

83
00:09:02,114 --> 00:09:04,143
willfully disobey the same.

84
00:09:04,168 --> 00:09:06,979
With the result that injuries
were sustained by the crew.

85
00:09:07,004 --> 00:09:10,184
A passenger was killed.
And the airplane destroyed.

86
00:09:10,364 --> 00:09:11,770
Charge two.

87
00:09:12,113 --> 00:09:14,863
Violation of the 96th Article of War.

88
00:09:15,409 --> 00:09:19,380
Specification. In that Jefferson
Young, second lieutenant, Air Corps,

89
00:09:19,405 --> 00:09:23,226
did at Marsh Field, California,
admit an unauthorized passenger,

90
00:09:23,251 --> 00:09:26,930
one Sally Vaughn, on
board a Flying Fortress airplane.

91
00:09:26,955 --> 00:09:29,173
In violation of existing regulations.

92
00:09:29,198 --> 00:09:32,423
And to the prejudice of
good order and military discipline.

93
00:09:34,134 --> 00:09:37,209
How does the accused plead
to Specification Charge One?

94
00:09:37,651 --> 00:09:39,155
Guilty, sir.

95
00:09:39,180 --> 00:09:41,804
What is the plea to
Specification Charge Two?

96
00:09:42,123 --> 00:09:44,835
Guilty, sir.
- That's not true, sir.

97
00:09:44,868 --> 00:09:46,503
Any further interruption

98
00:09:46,653 --> 00:09:49,549
will necessitate your removal
from the courtroom. Sit down.

99
00:09:51,759 --> 00:09:56,306
You have no further statement?
- No, sir. - Court will be closed.

100
00:09:56,953 --> 00:09:59,283
Let me see the
record of the accused.

101
00:10:00,880 --> 00:10:02,966
You must be crazy.
- Aw, skip it, Al.

102
00:10:02,991 --> 00:10:06,080
You're fixing yourself up for good.
- Let me take care of that.

103
00:10:24,835 --> 00:10:27,929
Guess I must be seeing things.
I thought I saw Carolyn. - Listen, Jeff.

104
00:10:27,964 --> 00:10:29,862
I'm not going to let you
toss out your job for my sake.

105
00:10:29,897 --> 00:10:31,243
I'm gonna go in and
tell 'em the whole story.

106
00:10:31,267 --> 00:10:34,782
One chirp out of you and I'll
break your neck. - Well, gentlemen.

107
00:10:35,168 --> 00:10:36,548
Here's the record.

108
00:10:38,271 --> 00:10:39,962
Jefferson Young the 3rd.

109
00:10:40,214 --> 00:10:44,128
Lawrenceville Preparatory School.
Yale University.

110
00:10:44,800 --> 00:10:48,478
Applied for Air Corps training
and was admitted to Randolph Field

111
00:10:48,503 --> 00:10:50,291
two years ago this spring.

112
00:10:59,027 --> 00:11:00,946
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>RANDOLPH
FIELD</b></font>

113
00:11:03,014 --> 00:11:06,236
<font color=#C0C0C0><b>CADETS WILL NOT USE
EAST END OF PARKING LOT</b></font>

114
00:11:20,896 --> 00:11:22,335
Give me your attention.

115
00:11:23,100 --> 00:11:24,014
Down here at Randolph,

116
00:11:24,164 --> 00:11:26,241
they don't care who you
are, or where you come from.

117
00:11:26,860 --> 00:11:28,993
The Army is only
interested in two things.

118
00:11:29,567 --> 00:11:31,730
Can you fly?
Will you make an officer?

119
00:11:31,993 --> 00:11:33,271
And they'll find out.

120
00:11:33,306 --> 00:11:35,486
And we upperclassmen
will try to help you learn,

121
00:11:35,636 --> 00:11:37,219
what we've learned
in the last four months.

122
00:11:38,077 --> 00:11:40,924
Before you report to the flight
surgeon for a physical recheck,

123
00:11:41,288 --> 00:11:43,416
take a look at the man
on either side of you.

124
00:11:46,709 --> 00:11:48,090
Go ahead. Take a good look.

125
00:11:51,209 --> 00:11:53,800
In four months, one
of you won't be here.

126
00:11:55,189 --> 00:11:57,755
Report to your
squad leaders. Dismissed.

127
00:12:05,898 --> 00:12:07,679
One out of three washed out.

128
00:12:07,704 --> 00:12:10,064
You two ought to toss a coin to
see which one he's talking about.

129
00:12:10,088 --> 00:12:13,774
Oh, he's talking about me.
Regulations say you can't be over 6'2".

130
00:12:13,799 --> 00:12:14,980
That's just what
I was when I enlisted.

131
00:12:15,004 --> 00:12:16,874
But I grew a half-inch
waiting to be admitted.

132
00:12:53,491 --> 00:12:54,524
Good morning.

133
00:12:55,668 --> 00:12:57,846
The boys will be
out flying pretty soon.

134
00:12:59,425 --> 00:13:00,941
You scared of flying?

135
00:13:02,247 --> 00:13:05,316
No, sir.
Scared of not flying.

136
00:13:05,341 --> 00:13:08,633
I know just how you
feel. I'm Colonel Riley.

137
00:13:09,590 --> 00:13:11,763
First man to go
up in a free balloon.

138
00:13:12,350 --> 00:13:16,327
1879. Went up on
half an hour's notice.

139
00:13:16,352 --> 00:13:19,045
All they told me
was to drop sandbags.

140
00:13:19,070 --> 00:13:20,600
And I dropped them.

141
00:13:20,625 --> 00:13:23,319
Floated 800 miles in five days.

142
00:13:23,344 --> 00:13:26,367
When I gave my report
to President Ulysses S. Grant.

143
00:13:26,392 --> 00:13:29,051
I said the air.
The air is the thing.

144
00:13:29,076 --> 00:13:32,735
It's here to stay.
- I hope I stay with it.

145
00:13:32,760 --> 00:13:35,640
Well, son. If you run
into a stall, just call on me.

146
00:13:35,665 --> 00:13:37,085
I've been giving the Army

147
00:13:37,110 --> 00:13:40,122
expert advice on training
young pilots for the last 40 years.

148
00:13:40,147 --> 00:13:41,790
Hello, Sandbag.
- Hello.

149
00:13:43,830 --> 00:13:46,276
Aren't you a new
cadet, mister? - Yes, sir.

150
00:13:46,301 --> 00:13:49,181
You're supposed to be the hospital
taking a physical recheck. Aren't you?

151
00:13:49,649 --> 00:13:51,477
Yes, sir.
- Weill, take off.

152
00:13:53,535 --> 00:13:56,897
I'm going to dress down
that young upstart for not saluting me.

153
00:13:57,623 --> 00:14:00,280
That's all, young man.
- Yes, sir.

154
00:14:05,507 --> 00:14:08,359
Song you got the makings
of an officer and a gentleman.

155
00:14:09,624 --> 00:14:10,655
Thank you, sir.

156
00:14:21,956 --> 00:14:23,144
Hey, you better quit stalling.

157
00:14:23,168 --> 00:14:26,753
And get over the flight surgeon's
office for that recheck. - I'm going.

158
00:14:27,514 --> 00:14:29,589
You f- Why not?

159
00:14:29,614 --> 00:14:32,105
Nothing the matter with us.
- You sure are lucky.

160
00:14:32,106 --> 00:14:33,270
I don't smoke. I don't drink.

161
00:14:33,295 --> 00:14:36,989
I don't break training for four years.
And what happens? I'm overgrown.

162
00:14:38,389 --> 00:14:40,052
You know, I had the same trouble.

163
00:14:40,077 --> 00:14:42,624
Till I find out if you stand
at attention for a while.

164
00:14:42,649 --> 00:14:46,608
And jump up and down, you can
maybe jog a half inch off. - Yeah?

165
00:14:46,633 --> 00:14:49,225
Sure. Jockeys do it all the time.

166
00:14:51,268 --> 00:14:55,147
Do you mean like this?
- Yeah, only higher.  Oh.

167
00:14:59,805 --> 00:15:02,672
Well, fancy that.
Say, uh, uh.

168
00:15:02,697 --> 00:15:04,721
Ludlow. Al Ludlow.
- Cassidy.

169
00:15:05,922 --> 00:15:07,867
He's a polo player.
- So what?

170
00:15:07,892 --> 00:15:11,024
J. Y.? Oh, yeah.
Jeff Young the 3rd.  Eight goals.

171
00:15:11,049 --> 00:15:14,681
He's filthy rich, Ludlow.
- 8 goals and 8 mission bucks.

172
00:15:14,682 --> 00:15:16,924
Is that the way they rate him?
- Say, tell me, Young.

173
00:15:16,949 --> 00:15:19,197
What is a tough guy like
you want down here anyway.

174
00:15:19,222 --> 00:15:22,550
Here's a good place to find
out fast just how tough you are.

175
00:15:22,575 --> 00:15:24,308
Oh, well, I don't have to find out.

176
00:15:24,597 --> 00:15:27,706
That this is what they gave me for
being the toughest guy in the Big Ten.

177
00:15:28,541 --> 00:15:32,246
Too bad they don't have
cheerleaders down here. - Yeah.

178
00:15:33,596 --> 00:15:34,649
Yeah.

179
00:15:35,657 --> 00:15:36,541
And here's the shoe

180
00:15:36,566 --> 00:15:39,086
that kicked the winning field
goal against Notre Dame last year.

181
00:15:39,234 --> 00:15:40,797
When you get back
from the flight surgeon's,

182
00:15:40,947 --> 00:15:44,792
I want to show you my baby
pictures. Aw, swell. - If you get back.

183
00:15:44,990 --> 00:15:46,125
Yeah.

184
00:15:50,015 --> 00:15:53,414
Well, come on, baby.
Bounce. Bounce. - Oh.

185
00:15:53,439 --> 00:15:56,199
Oh yeah. I wish I'd
known about this before.

186
00:15:56,200 --> 00:15:58,240
I could have been doing
it in the train coming down.

187
00:16:10,532 --> 00:16:13,466
I see where it's going to be awful
noisy sleeping in the Hall of Fame.

188
00:16:14,509 --> 00:16:15,817
Say, Ludlow.

189
00:16:17,895 --> 00:16:19,668
What did you do
before you came here?

190
00:16:20,485 --> 00:16:23,293
I was a mechanic.
Worked in garages.

191
00:16:23,318 --> 00:16:26,227
Airplane factories.
Sold.

192
00:16:26,252 --> 00:16:27,727
I tried just about everything.

193
00:16:28,117 --> 00:16:30,980
Well, uh, where'd you get
your two years college equivalent?

194
00:16:31,005 --> 00:16:34,092
Trade school? - Never
stayed long enough one place.

195
00:16:34,364 --> 00:16:37,271
I got a satchel full of diplomas
from correspondence schools.

196
00:16:37,830 --> 00:16:41,265
What brought you
down here? - I want to fly.

197
00:16:42,647 --> 00:16:44,069
As it would be.

198
00:16:54,283 --> 00:16:57,897
Say, uh. They really wouldn't wash a
man out for a half an inch, would they?

199
00:16:58,421 --> 00:17:01,086
Sonny, down here, they
wash you out for a bad haircut.

200
00:17:05,939 --> 00:17:06,939
Turn around.

201
00:17:11,882 --> 00:17:13,414
Straighten up.
- Oh, yes, sir.

202
00:17:14,956 --> 00:17:15,956
Ohh.

203
00:17:17,580 --> 00:17:19,882
What are plans after
you graduate, Cassidy?

204
00:17:19,883 --> 00:17:21,696
Oh, applying for a commission.

205
00:17:22,265 --> 00:17:25,290
Get a job with an airline,
maybe. - I suppose that...

206
00:17:26,097 --> 00:17:28,307
You mean I pass?
You mean I'm only 6'2"?

207
00:17:28,332 --> 00:17:29,735
You're six-two and a half.

208
00:17:29,736 --> 00:17:31,729
But since you added
the extra half-inch after you enlisted,

209
00:17:31,753 --> 00:17:34,214
I guess it's on the Army.
But don't grow anymore.

210
00:17:34,239 --> 00:17:36,480
Our airplanes don't
stretch. - Aw, I won't, sir.

211
00:17:36,505 --> 00:17:39,753
I mean I won't, sir.
Ha, I passed. I passed!

212
00:17:41,395 --> 00:17:45,137
My clothes.
I forgot my clothes, sir.

213
00:17:52,016 --> 00:17:55,626
What's the matter? Don't you like your
mechanic's outfit,  Mr. Jeff Young the 3rd?

214
00:17:55,651 --> 00:17:58,298
Hey, I'm in!
Hey, fellas. I'm in!

215
00:17:58,323 --> 00:18:01,627
I made it!
Hey, 82, out, 82, 54, hike!

216
00:18:03,902 --> 00:18:05,523
That's the play
that made me famous.

217
00:18:05,524 --> 00:18:07,934
Taking out two
guys at the same time.

218
00:18:11,850 --> 00:18:12,850
As you were.

219
00:18:21,787 --> 00:18:25,693
What? Where do you misters
think you are? At a freshman rally?

220
00:18:25,718 --> 00:18:29,406
This is the Army. We expect
you to act  in a military manner.

221
00:18:31,343 --> 00:18:32,429
Size?

222
00:18:33,822 --> 00:18:36,322
13. - 13? That'll have
to be special issue.

223
00:18:48,311 --> 00:18:50,759
Left face.
Right face.

224
00:18:51,024 --> 00:18:54,055
About face.
- Right face.

225
00:18:54,080 --> 00:18:56,884
Right face.
- Left face.

226
00:18:57,213 --> 00:19:00,260
Forward, march.
- To the rear, march.

227
00:19:00,285 --> 00:19:02,287
Forward, march.
Left - - March.

228
00:19:02,392 --> 00:19:04,206
Left... March.
Right, march.

229
00:19:14,043 --> 00:19:15,684
Good day.

230
00:19:27,531 --> 00:19:31,382
You're turning too fast. Don't forget
air speed until you stall into a spin.

231
00:19:32,212 --> 00:19:34,829
Now recover from
your spin and try it again.

232
00:19:43,743 --> 00:19:44,743
Be seated.

233
00:19:52,560 --> 00:19:53,931
Take off at will.

234
00:20:06,191 --> 00:20:07,801
What's the matter,
mister. You sick?

235
00:20:08,196 --> 00:20:12,034
No, uh. No, sir.
I made a terrible mistake.

236
00:20:12,068 --> 00:20:15,199
What's that, mister? - I thought
they taught you to fly down here, sir.

237
00:20:15,223 --> 00:20:17,771
They do. You'll meet your
flying instructor tomorrow.

238
00:20:17,795 --> 00:20:20,106
Oh, swell.

239
00:21:03,488 --> 00:21:04,785
Cadet Young, sir.

240
00:21:06,469 --> 00:21:09,477
Cadet Ludlow, sir.
- Cadet Cassidy, sir.

241
00:21:10,688 --> 00:21:14,369
Cadet Masters, sir.
- Cadet Wilcox, sir.

242
00:21:15,948 --> 00:21:19,275
Now we'll drop all that.
I want you to relax.

243
00:21:20,574 --> 00:21:24,449
This is an airplane. I'm going
to teach you to fly one, I hope.

244
00:21:26,092 --> 00:21:27,717
This is the ship will start out on.

245
00:21:27,742 --> 00:21:30,318
So let's climb aboard
and look her over.

246
00:21:39,657 --> 00:21:41,485
I'll tell you everything
I know about it.

247
00:21:41,510 --> 00:21:43,782
All I ask is your strict attention.

248
00:21:43,807 --> 00:21:46,916
I expect you to make mistakes.
But don't make excuses.

249
00:21:46,964 --> 00:21:49,721
That's the stick.
That controls things.

250
00:21:50,375 --> 00:21:52,667
You move it forward,
your nose goes down.

251
00:21:52,692 --> 00:21:54,503
You pull it back,
your nose comes up.

252
00:21:54,528 --> 00:21:58,481
These instruments and controls look
complicated. But a week from now, they won't.

253
00:21:58,506 --> 00:22:02,028
Your flight instruments are
in the center. Bank and turn.

254
00:22:02,053 --> 00:22:04,692
Air speed.
Rate of climb and altimeter.

255
00:22:04,717 --> 00:22:06,717
All right.
Any questions?

256
00:22:08,975 --> 00:22:11,820
Good. You, Young.
I'll take you first.

257
00:22:18,287 --> 00:22:21,261
All we do this morning is
to shake hands with flying.

258
00:22:21,286 --> 00:22:24,693
Begin to feel at home in the plane.
Get familiar with the sky.

259
00:22:25,609 --> 00:22:26,850
Get into your chute.

260
00:22:29,734 --> 00:22:30,968
Buckle your belt.

261
00:23:07,675 --> 00:23:10,156
All right, Young.
Follow me on the controls.

262
00:23:14,783 --> 00:23:18,568
Lightly. Lightly. We're flying.
Not hauling a load of cement.

263
00:23:50,955 --> 00:23:53,666
You may be good enough
to come this close, Cassidy.

264
00:23:53,691 --> 00:23:55,041
But I'm not.

265
00:24:17,395 --> 00:24:20,497
Get off the roller coaster,
will you, Ludlow?

266
00:24:30,884 --> 00:24:33,111
Confound it, Ludlow.
Hold your speed constant.

267
00:24:33,136 --> 00:24:35,034
If you're gonna dive her in,
dive her in.

268
00:24:35,059 --> 00:24:38,309
If you're gonna stall her in,
stall her in. But don't vacillate.

269
00:24:38,872 --> 00:24:42,411
You can't learn accuracy
without a constant glide.

270
00:24:42,436 --> 00:24:46,248
Land shorter this time.
Stop using the whole field.

271
00:24:47,514 --> 00:24:51,326
Fly the airplane, Ludlow.
Don't let the airplane fly you.

272
00:24:53,473 --> 00:24:55,156
Here come Al and Mercer.

273
00:24:57,794 --> 00:24:59,320
One.

274
00:25:01,273 --> 00:25:04,189
Two.
Three.

275
00:25:04,214 --> 00:25:05,540
Four.

276
00:25:05,994 --> 00:25:09,369
It ought to scramble those eggs
Mercer had for breakfast. - Yeah.

277
00:25:09,394 --> 00:25:12,284
Hey, Jimmy. Chalk up a
buck against Mr. Ludlow.

278
00:25:12,309 --> 00:25:13,745
Four stars coming up.

279
00:25:15,637 --> 00:25:18,661
Your Ludlow is way out ahead
in the Dumbbell Derby.

280
00:25:18,686 --> 00:25:21,255
Oh, what difference does it
make how good or bad you are.

281
00:25:21,280 --> 00:25:23,639
They don't set us
up to for solo. - Yeah.

282
00:25:24,890 --> 00:25:27,171
Well, maybe they're going
to wash out the whole battalion.

283
00:25:28,748 --> 00:25:30,951
Hey! Hey!
As you were, mister.

284
00:25:30,976 --> 00:25:32,108
As you were.

285
00:25:35,861 --> 00:25:38,820
Oh, hey. Four stars.
Pay up a dollar for the kitty.

286
00:25:39,492 --> 00:25:41,861
I'll pay you up in the room.
- Okay.

287
00:25:41,908 --> 00:25:43,673
We ought to make
you a wholesale price.

288
00:25:43,698 --> 00:25:46,876
You use too much rudder on a left turn,
you feel the wind on your right cheek.

289
00:25:46,901 --> 00:25:48,997
You don't even it up,
you feel it on the other cheek.

290
00:25:51,237 --> 00:25:55,151
What am I doing here anyway?
This is no place for a dumb mechanic.

291
00:25:55,176 --> 00:25:58,214
Don't take that attitude, Al.
Shucks, I'm dumb too but.

292
00:25:58,239 --> 00:26:00,276
What the heck
you can't buck nature.

293
00:26:01,398 --> 00:26:02,887
Young.
- Yeah.

294
00:26:02,912 --> 00:26:05,340
On the line. Right away.
Solo.  - Okay.

295
00:26:07,086 --> 00:26:08,959
Got it?
- Huh?

296
00:26:08,984 --> 00:26:12,389
Jeff's gonna solo.
Hey, fellas, Jeff's gonna solo!

297
00:26:14,727 --> 00:26:15,727
Jeff's gonna solo!

298
00:26:18,920 --> 00:26:21,206
Break the ice.
- Fly the pants off that thing.

299
00:26:21,281 --> 00:26:23,267
We're rooting for you.
- Don't hog me, boys.

300
00:26:23,292 --> 00:26:25,517
Give me air, will ya?
- Don't think too much.

301
00:26:25,542 --> 00:26:27,558
Just relax.
- Go out there and show 'em.

302
00:26:27,583 --> 00:26:30,348
Give 'em the old power play right through
center. And remember, keep your head.

303
00:26:30,372 --> 00:26:31,899
Don't worry about me.
All I got to do is this.

304
00:26:31,900 --> 00:26:35,128
Climb a little faster. And glide a
little further. - Don't get nervous.

305
00:26:35,153 --> 00:26:36,761
I'm not nervous.
- No.

306
00:26:36,786 --> 00:26:39,481
What do you got that flying suit
on backwards for then? - Huh?

307
00:26:43,059 --> 00:26:45,574
Come on. Let him do it by
himself. He's a big boy now.

308
00:26:45,609 --> 00:26:46,924
Gimme the other arm.

309
00:26:47,622 --> 00:26:51,114
What are you thinking about?
- Young.  - Yes, sir.

310
00:26:53,181 --> 00:26:56,523
Come on, Young. You're going out
to solo. Not to get married. - Yes, sir.

311
00:26:57,844 --> 00:27:00,111
Good luck, Jeff.
- Thanks.

312
00:27:37,377 --> 00:27:38,377
Ya.

313
00:27:39,428 --> 00:27:40,428
Boy oh boy.

314
00:28:03,209 --> 00:28:05,701
Flier.
- Mickey.

315
00:28:07,574 --> 00:28:10,615
Oh, would you mind? You're
casting a shadow in my reflector.

316
00:28:23,797 --> 00:28:26,120
What's the matter? Haven't
you ever seen a bomber before?

317
00:28:26,145 --> 00:28:28,122
Never with landing gear like that.

318
00:28:31,938 --> 00:28:35,059
Aren't you making kind of free
with that camera around an Army Post?

319
00:28:35,940 --> 00:28:39,186
Look. I'm trying to
make a series of pictures.

320
00:28:39,928 --> 00:28:41,584
For a national magazine.

321
00:28:41,609 --> 00:28:44,764
With full permission and cooperation
of the United States Army.

322
00:28:45,273 --> 00:28:48,281
We'll set up over there for the next
few pictures. - Okay, Miss Bartlett.

323
00:28:55,992 --> 00:28:58,258
Bartlett. Bartlett. Bartlett.

324
00:28:59,195 --> 00:29:00,195
Oh.

325
00:29:02,617 --> 00:29:05,133
See here. Carolyn Bartlett. I know you.

326
00:29:05,158 --> 00:29:07,947
Photography's dynamic
symmetry girl, yes.

327
00:29:07,972 --> 00:29:10,706
Kansas corn silos.
Steam turbines.

328
00:29:10,738 --> 00:29:13,858
Private eyes on the blast
furnace, sure. - Yes.

329
00:29:13,893 --> 00:29:17,610
And I must say I find you even
more interesting than Junior Bergman.

330
00:29:28,817 --> 00:29:30,951
Oh, no no. As you were.
- Hey, dopey.

331
00:29:32,652 --> 00:29:35,302
You're in clover.
She likes class poses.

332
00:29:35,904 --> 00:29:37,904
You know her?
- Do I know her?

333
00:29:38,108 --> 00:29:39,147
Come here.

334
00:29:43,164 --> 00:29:45,226
Miss Bartlett. I'd like
you to meet Mr. Cassidy.

335
00:29:45,250 --> 00:29:47,142
How do you do?
- How are you?

336
00:29:47,970 --> 00:29:49,883
Can I help?
- At what?

337
00:29:51,111 --> 00:29:53,658
Yes. Would you like to
hold my reflector for me?

338
00:29:53,682 --> 00:29:55,659
Oh, yes, ma'am. Here.
- Mickey, give it to Mr. Cassidy.

339
00:29:55,683 --> 00:29:57,759
And get my other camera,
will you? - Okay, Miss Bartlett.

340
00:29:57,784 --> 00:30:01,050
Hang it over here.
Now there you are.

341
00:30:01,776 --> 00:30:04,089
A little more.
Come on. Some more.

342
00:30:04,114 --> 00:30:07,348
Now that's fine.
Now you just hold it there.

343
00:30:07,349 --> 00:30:10,245
Cassidy.
Cassidy!

344
00:30:10,511 --> 00:30:12,823
Here, sir.
Hold that, will ya?

345
00:30:14,085 --> 00:30:16,027
Now's your chance
to get a picture of some real flying.

346
00:30:16,051 --> 00:30:17,693
My instructor can't wait
to get in the plane with me.

347
00:30:17,717 --> 00:30:20,801
It gives him a chance to
catch up on his sleep. Oof.

348
00:30:29,552 --> 00:30:32,333
You know it surprises me every
time that guy gets off the ground.

349
00:30:32,358 --> 00:30:35,810
Really? He seems
rather capable to me.

350
00:30:37,244 --> 00:30:39,788
Yes, sir.
- You're wasting time.

351
00:30:39,813 --> 00:30:42,382
You stand by to meet the ship when
you're scheduled next. - Yes, sir.

352
00:30:42,407 --> 00:30:43,788
In the back.

353
00:30:50,692 --> 00:30:54,571
Take me out to a practice area and
show me some improvement. - Yes, sir.

354
00:31:22,575 --> 00:31:23,906
Cassidy.

355
00:31:24,258 --> 00:31:26,617
Your progress is a fair average.

356
00:31:27,550 --> 00:31:29,642
You're a little bit on the cocky side.

357
00:31:30,439 --> 00:31:34,837
Just in case your head is getting a
little bit too big for your buttocks.

358
00:31:34,870 --> 00:31:38,605
I'm going to show you a couple of things
that you'll have to learn very soon.

359
00:31:39,398 --> 00:31:42,191
This first is what we call a slow roll.

360
00:31:43,058 --> 00:31:44,058
Check your belt.

361
00:31:46,505 --> 00:31:47,505
Okay, sir.

362
00:31:51,278 --> 00:31:52,278
Stop.

363
00:32:16,329 --> 00:32:20,196
All right, Cassidy.
Climb back to 3000 feet.

364
00:32:20,221 --> 00:32:23,096
We'll do it again and you'll
follow me through on the control.

365
00:32:32,936 --> 00:32:35,834
I said climb her back to 3000 feet.

366
00:33:12,520 --> 00:33:14,840
Lt. Clankton speaking.
- Hello.

367
00:33:14,865 --> 00:33:19,043
Flying Cadet Cassidy wishes to report
he just fell out of an airplane, sir.

368
00:33:19,068 --> 00:33:20,068
All right.

369
00:33:24,789 --> 00:33:25,922
What?!

370
00:33:27,977 --> 00:33:31,508
You men who have soloed are
starting to feel like pretty hot pilots.

371
00:33:32,236 --> 00:33:34,298
During the past week
several minor violations

372
00:33:34,323 --> 00:33:36,635
of flying regulations have cropped up.

373
00:33:36,986 --> 00:33:40,761
One pretty serious one.
So go easy on trains.

374
00:33:41,433 --> 00:33:44,425
Cattle.
Individual combat.

375
00:33:44,450 --> 00:33:47,480
And outside loops.
That's all.

376
00:33:57,548 --> 00:33:58,555
Cassidy.

377
00:34:00,026 --> 00:34:02,680
Cassidy!
- Oh, yes, sir.

378
00:34:04,337 --> 00:34:06,893
Stay with us, will ya?
- Yes, sir.

379
00:34:11,126 --> 00:34:14,268
It's a good thing that big
dumbbell's a natural born flier.

380
00:34:19,585 --> 00:34:21,535
You men that haven't soloed it yet.

381
00:34:22,688 --> 00:34:24,246
I'd like to offer you a little tip.

382
00:34:24,524 --> 00:34:26,758
The Army has just
so much time to devote

383
00:34:26,815 --> 00:34:29,400
to finding out whether
each of you is a flier or not.

384
00:34:30,876 --> 00:34:32,821
So make every minute in the air count.

385
00:34:34,565 --> 00:34:36,542
That's all.
Ludlow.

386
00:34:37,935 --> 00:34:39,096
I want to see you a minute.

387
00:34:45,386 --> 00:34:47,465
Would you say that
I know my business?

388
00:34:47,998 --> 00:34:49,933
I think so around here, sir.

389
00:34:50,690 --> 00:34:52,386
And why am I losing out with a man

390
00:34:52,411 --> 00:34:54,543
that's got everything
it takes to make a flier?

391
00:34:55,260 --> 00:34:58,076
What's on your mind,
Ludlow? Family?

392
00:34:58,341 --> 00:35:00,513
Money?
Women?

393
00:35:00,538 --> 00:35:03,021
Just tell me I'm through, sir.
I can take it.

394
00:35:04,579 --> 00:35:05,960
Why don't you forget her?

395
00:35:07,369 --> 00:35:11,215
I don't know what you're
talking about, sir. - I think I do.

396
00:35:14,445 --> 00:35:18,363
I can't forget her. I keep seeing her
the way she was  the night we busted it up.

397
00:35:18,388 --> 00:35:20,761
I keep hearing
her say you're a flop.

398
00:35:20,786 --> 00:35:23,619
You'll never be anything
but a $15 a week grease monkey.

399
00:35:24,346 --> 00:35:27,411
I was sore too. I told her
to beat it and she went.

400
00:35:28,465 --> 00:35:29,880
And with another guy.

401
00:35:31,297 --> 00:35:34,225
She said she was
going places. And she will.

402
00:35:34,250 --> 00:35:35,741
The quickest way she can.

403
00:35:37,211 --> 00:35:39,946
After that, I threw off
my job and pulled out.

404
00:35:41,064 --> 00:35:43,883
Things weren't going
to be going so well.

405
00:35:44,481 --> 00:35:46,461
So I kept telling myself.
It's just bad breaks.

406
00:35:47,618 --> 00:35:50,447
But after a while I began to
wonder. Maybe it was me.

407
00:35:51,981 --> 00:35:53,439
I always wanted to fly.

408
00:35:54,088 --> 00:35:56,080
That's one of the reasons
I joined the Air Corps.

409
00:35:57,144 --> 00:36:00,457
But it was more than that, sir.
You see I have to know about myself.

410
00:36:00,482 --> 00:36:02,511
If I wash out, then she's right.

411
00:36:06,232 --> 00:36:08,047
I never told that to anybody, sir.

412
00:36:11,200 --> 00:36:12,497
Suppose she is right.

413
00:36:14,108 --> 00:36:17,749
I know a lot of swell guys that
are $15 a week grease monkeys.

414
00:36:19,593 --> 00:36:22,858
Now the trouble with you is
that you're trying too hard.

415
00:36:23,833 --> 00:36:26,594
Relax.
Stop tensing up.

416
00:36:27,352 --> 00:36:30,282
It's part of learning to fly.
The big part.

417
00:36:30,307 --> 00:36:32,828
I know that, sir.
- Ludlow. Look.

418
00:36:34,051 --> 00:36:36,627
Fliers are just like all other men.

419
00:36:37,365 --> 00:36:39,869
And they fall into
the same two groups.

420
00:36:40,440 --> 00:36:42,793
Those that women have made happy.

421
00:36:42,818 --> 00:36:44,785
Those that women
have made unhappy.

422
00:36:45,828 --> 00:36:48,136
But whether they're
lucky that way or not.

423
00:36:48,638 --> 00:36:52,255
They just keep plugging along
at their job like everybody else does.

424
00:36:53,599 --> 00:36:57,778
Now if you can't forget
this girl, don't.

425
00:36:58,183 --> 00:37:01,944
Stop trying. But get
this through your head.

426
00:37:03,033 --> 00:37:05,288
You can still make a whale of a flier.

427
00:37:10,287 --> 00:37:11,358
Ludlow.

428
00:37:11,949 --> 00:37:15,256
I'm sending you up for a check ride
with a flight commander tomorrow.

429
00:37:15,959 --> 00:37:18,147
I've told him I thought
you'd make a pilot.

430
00:37:19,443 --> 00:37:20,756
I still think so.

431
00:37:22,031 --> 00:37:24,109
Now don't make a monkey out of me.

432
00:37:33,943 --> 00:37:37,123
Catastrophic instability is
a characteristic of an aircraft,

433
00:37:37,148 --> 00:37:40,232
which having deviated from level flight
tends to increase the deviation.

434
00:37:40,257 --> 00:37:42,234
Look, Jeff.
I've soloed, haven't I?

435
00:37:42,259 --> 00:37:44,070
Now why do I
have to learn this junk?

436
00:37:44,095 --> 00:37:47,367
You want to know what you're
doing, don't you? - Hey Jeff?  - Yeah.

437
00:37:47,392 --> 00:37:49,330
You're want over at
Lt. Roger's office right away.

438
00:37:49,354 --> 00:37:51,415
Ha, he must need
some expert advice.

439
00:38:02,408 --> 00:38:03,994
Cadet Young reporting, sir.

440
00:38:04,019 --> 00:38:07,376
Perhaps you know about Miss Bartlett's
presence at the post, Young. - Yes, sir.

441
00:38:07,401 --> 00:38:10,337
She's looking for someone
to photograph as the average cadet here.

442
00:38:10,362 --> 00:38:12,636
You've been selected.
- Who? Me, sir?

443
00:38:12,661 --> 00:38:13,957
You will cooperate with Miss Bartlett

444
00:38:13,981 --> 00:38:15,668
whenever it doesn't
interfere with your duties.

445
00:38:15,692 --> 00:38:19,348
Miss Bartlett is a very charming girl.
It was nice of her to select me.

446
00:38:19,373 --> 00:38:21,380
But Miss Bartlett didn't
select you. The Army did.

447
00:38:23,648 --> 00:38:26,333
I came down here to
be a flier, sir. Not a model.

448
00:38:26,358 --> 00:38:28,874
Did you ever see any
of those screwy pictures she takes?

449
00:38:28,899 --> 00:38:31,360
Mr. Young, we didn't call you
here to give a class as an art critic.

450
00:38:31,384 --> 00:38:33,992
This is official.
- Yes, sir.

451
00:38:37,352 --> 00:38:39,859
I'm so sorry to
trouble you, Mr. Young.

452
00:38:40,758 --> 00:38:42,391
It's no trouble at all.

453
00:38:42,416 --> 00:38:44,916
Now would you mind
stepping over by the window?

454
00:38:47,978 --> 00:38:51,150
Hmm. Turn your
profile into the light.

455
00:38:54,855 --> 00:38:57,441
A bit afraid of the mouth.

456
00:39:00,767 --> 00:39:03,112
And the line of the jaw there.

457
00:39:07,067 --> 00:39:11,052
Oh, dear.
What do you think, Mickey?

458
00:39:11,325 --> 00:39:13,052
Lean over so he can see.

459
00:39:16,881 --> 00:39:19,787
I don't think the chin's gonna do it.

460
00:39:28,562 --> 00:39:31,320
What was the name of the cadet
with you yesterday?

461
00:39:31,813 --> 00:39:32,965
Cassidy.

462
00:39:33,634 --> 00:39:37,197
I really feel it that Cadet Cassidy
might be more suitable.

463
00:39:37,222 --> 00:39:39,697
That's all, Young.
Send Cadet Cassidy over.

464
00:39:39,722 --> 00:39:40,814
Yes, sir.

465
00:40:03,244 --> 00:40:04,377
Now look, dopey.

466
00:40:04,402 --> 00:40:07,386
Catastrophic instability
is the characteristic

467
00:40:07,411 --> 00:40:10,714
of an aircraft
which having deviated from...

468
00:40:11,771 --> 00:40:14,528
Hey, I think I got it now.
Catastrophic... - Yeah.

469
00:40:18,092 --> 00:40:19,421
What's the matter?

470
00:40:22,335 --> 00:40:25,569
Maybe I'm crazy.
- What's the matter?

471
00:40:25,594 --> 00:40:28,085
They want you over at
the public relations office right away.

472
00:40:28,851 --> 00:40:31,593
Masters, would you take
this Greek god to Ronson's office.

473
00:40:31,618 --> 00:40:33,352
But don't chip the profile.

474
00:40:33,377 --> 00:40:35,649
Come on. Hurry up.
They're waiting for you.

475
00:40:35,674 --> 00:40:38,541
The Lady of the Lens
is on the loose. - Oh.

476
00:40:38,566 --> 00:40:41,188
Ohh! Lady of the Lens? Ha, ha.

477
00:40:41,189 --> 00:40:43,636
Come on, professors.
Come on.

478
00:40:50,488 --> 00:40:53,105
He's going to be
the great lover of the Air Corps.

479
00:40:53,566 --> 00:40:55,105
Roll up your flaps, will ya?

480
00:40:56,071 --> 00:40:57,886
That's nice talk to a hot pilot.

481
00:40:58,510 --> 00:41:01,825
You're in a class all by yourself,
aren't you? - That's what they tell me.

482
00:41:01,850 --> 00:41:04,661
Just watch me up there for a
while and maybe you'll solo too.

483
00:41:07,817 --> 00:41:10,200
Aw, come on, Al.
Put it in the hanger.

484
00:41:10,225 --> 00:41:12,747
Gimme those.
I told you to lay off.

485
00:41:14,247 --> 00:41:16,341
Hey, you can't quit now.
I'm on the deck.

486
00:41:18,630 --> 00:41:21,888
Ludlow.
Break it up. Break it up.

487
00:41:23,420 --> 00:41:25,443
You're supposed to be
a gentleman down here, Ludlow.

488
00:41:25,467 --> 00:41:28,164
You're not in the garage now. - You
don't have to tell me where I belong.

489
00:41:28,188 --> 00:41:30,499
Or what I'm going back to.
But before I go, I...

490
00:41:31,891 --> 00:41:33,313
Lucky he caught you, mister.

491
00:41:33,510 --> 00:41:35,994
They wash you out fast down here
for striking an upperclassman.

492
00:41:36,322 --> 00:41:38,627
Now what's this all about?
Who started it? - I did, sir.

493
00:41:38,652 --> 00:41:41,120
We had a little argument.
I got sore and I popped him.

494
00:41:41,590 --> 00:41:44,397
I don't blame him for losing his head.
- You report to the orderly room

495
00:41:44,421 --> 00:41:47,144
with proper uniform to walk
a punishment tour. - Yes, sir.

496
00:41:47,861 --> 00:41:50,614
You stuck your neck out, mister.
But you're in enough trouble.

497
00:41:50,639 --> 00:41:53,116
We'll skip it this time.
That's all.

498
00:42:01,305 --> 00:42:05,149
You don't have to take any
wraps for me. - I'm a real chump.

499
00:42:05,642 --> 00:42:07,025
I hate to see anybody get washed out

500
00:42:07,049 --> 00:42:08,782
before they had a chance to do
what they came down here for.

501
00:42:08,806 --> 00:42:11,884
What's the difference? They'll send
me up in the washing machine tomorrow.

502
00:42:15,564 --> 00:42:18,377
I'm sorry I put the rib on.
I know just how you feel.

503
00:42:19,214 --> 00:42:21,753
That's a laugh.
How can you know?

504
00:42:21,778 --> 00:42:25,292
You've never been in
a storm in your life. - No?

505
00:42:25,317 --> 00:42:27,683
I've been in a storm
ever since I came here.

506
00:42:32,450 --> 00:42:34,130
Every time I walk
down that flying line.

507
00:42:34,155 --> 00:42:36,286
And see those faces,
they nearly drive me nuts.

508
00:42:36,866 --> 00:42:40,631
300 guys all daring Jeff Young the
3rd to be as good as Joe Doakes.

509
00:42:43,463 --> 00:42:46,084
I never figured you
were afraid of anything.

510
00:42:47,370 --> 00:42:48,703
I tell you something else.

511
00:42:49,701 --> 00:42:51,781
The louder I talk,
the more scared I am.

512
00:42:52,750 --> 00:42:54,469
That's strictly
between you and me.

513
00:43:04,778 --> 00:43:07,997
Here.
Try wearing these tomorrow.

514
00:43:08,954 --> 00:43:10,236
They were lucky for me.

515
00:43:12,358 --> 00:43:14,751
Keep swinging, Al.
You still gotta chance.

516
00:43:16,579 --> 00:43:19,055
Now watch me talk
as I'm out walking the tour.

517
00:43:43,980 --> 00:43:45,301
Would you look up please?

518
00:43:48,996 --> 00:43:50,082
Thank you.

519
00:43:50,884 --> 00:43:53,837
Can you suggest any other
points of interest, Mr. Cassidy?

520
00:44:05,346 --> 00:44:07,298
Ludlow. You're next.

521
00:44:09,244 --> 00:44:11,822
It's gonna seem funny
not getting in with these anymore?

522
00:44:13,079 --> 00:44:14,699
What are you talking about?

523
00:44:14,724 --> 00:44:17,894
The seat of those pants will be worn
out before you turn that chute in.

524
00:44:19,667 --> 00:44:23,175
Yeah, I'm not kidding myself.
I picked Grady.

525
00:44:23,466 --> 00:44:26,052
Collins.
Anderson.

526
00:44:26,995 --> 00:44:29,990
When they send you up in the washing
machine, it's a one-way ticket home.

527
00:44:30,015 --> 00:44:32,327
The flight commander's
ready for you now, Ludlow.

528
00:44:37,811 --> 00:44:39,030
Come on. Climb in.

529
00:44:53,467 --> 00:44:54,568
I can't do it.

530
00:44:56,107 --> 00:44:58,388
I know I'm through.
Why do they have to drag it out?

531
00:44:58,413 --> 00:45:00,467
You're not through.
So why lie down and quit?

532
00:45:01,786 --> 00:45:03,021
I'm not a quitter.

533
00:45:04,210 --> 00:45:05,609
I know when I'm licked.

534
00:45:07,867 --> 00:45:10,140
Give me out of this thing.

535
00:45:10,437 --> 00:45:13,742
You report to that flying line if I have
to smack you down and carry you there.

536
00:45:14,009 --> 00:45:16,079
You came here to fly.
You're gonna fly.

537
00:45:16,930 --> 00:45:20,290
Now dump that flight commander into
the ship and ride the pants off him.

538
00:45:21,454 --> 00:45:22,564
Come on.

539
00:45:31,137 --> 00:45:35,044
Hey fellas, congratulate me. They
just passed me on my...  pylon eight.

540
00:45:35,069 --> 00:45:38,242
What's the matter with him?
- Only bad news out there.

541
00:45:38,267 --> 00:45:40,383
The worst.
- Yep.

542
00:45:41,541 --> 00:45:44,519
Did you hear him cry on his
pillow last night? He's a funny guy.

543
00:45:44,544 --> 00:45:46,939
Yeah, you're funny too.
Like a wing breaking off.

544
00:45:46,940 --> 00:45:48,519
What did I say?
- Oh, shut up.

545
00:45:58,290 --> 00:45:59,883
Cadet Ludlow reporting, sir.

546
00:46:04,790 --> 00:46:05,790
Ludlow.

547
00:46:06,774 --> 00:46:08,852
Before I send you up
to the flight commander,

548
00:46:09,080 --> 00:46:13,023
I want you to take
the ship up alone. - Alone?

549
00:46:13,665 --> 00:46:14,908
You heard me.

550
00:46:34,023 --> 00:46:36,290
He's going up solo.
Come on, Al.

551
00:46:36,314 --> 00:46:37,648
Allah, be merciful.

552
00:47:01,159 --> 00:47:02,300
He's in trouble.

553
00:47:09,687 --> 00:47:13,005
Takeoff. There's a BT in trouble
beyond the south end of the field.

554
00:47:25,562 --> 00:47:26,757
My motor's conked.

555
00:47:30,472 --> 00:47:32,173
Get the nose down.
Get it down.

556
00:47:32,198 --> 00:47:34,837
Gotta keep flying speed.
Pick a field and relax.

557
00:47:36,502 --> 00:47:39,455
There's one.
No good.

558
00:47:40,946 --> 00:47:43,409
It's downwind.
Find another one quick.

559
00:47:44,704 --> 00:47:46,354
Only got 400 feet.

560
00:47:46,596 --> 00:47:48,801
Come on. I can get in that one.

561
00:47:50,967 --> 00:47:52,074
Turn now.

562
00:47:53,422 --> 00:47:56,467
Don't change your mind.
Turn.

563
00:47:56,631 --> 00:47:58,467
Relax.
Loosen up.

564
00:47:58,529 --> 00:48:02,132
That field's small. Have to
cut those treetops and fish later.

565
00:48:02,164 --> 00:48:04,139
Cut in a little soon
now and stay high.

566
00:48:04,374 --> 00:48:07,077
You can kill altitude. But you can't
get it back without your motor.

567
00:48:09,923 --> 00:48:12,137
Keep flying speed and relax.

568
00:48:13,086 --> 00:48:14,954
Now fishtail her.

569
00:48:22,407 --> 00:48:24,525
Still too fast.
Once more.

570
00:48:30,059 --> 00:48:32,118
That's better.
Okay. Level out.

571
00:48:32,143 --> 00:48:34,715
Drop her in.
Don't dive at the ground.

572
00:48:34,750 --> 00:48:37,524
Careful. Careful.
Don't hit those trees.

573
00:48:42,690 --> 00:48:45,622
You have to switch before you
hit. Maybe I can ground loop her.

574
00:48:45,647 --> 00:48:47,812
Hit that left brake.
Hit it.

575
00:49:08,485 --> 00:49:11,165
Ha, ha, ha, ha.

576
00:49:16,298 --> 00:49:19,347
Are you all right?
- Sure.

577
00:49:19,903 --> 00:49:21,532
Okay, was it?

578
00:49:28,689 --> 00:49:30,790
What happened, Ludlow?
Motor conk out on you?

579
00:49:30,815 --> 00:49:34,064
Yes, sir. - You got plenty of
gas and the valve is turned on.

580
00:49:34,089 --> 00:49:35,470
It must have been a vapor lock.

581
00:49:36,970 --> 00:49:39,251
Well, we can fly her out of
here. We'll have to truck her.

582
00:49:39,723 --> 00:49:41,963
I don't know how you got her
in here without a shoe horn.

583
00:49:43,771 --> 00:49:47,667
Well, Ludlow. Now you see the value of
knowing  how to make a short approach.

584
00:49:48,073 --> 00:49:49,112
Yes, sir.

585
00:49:52,067 --> 00:49:53,372
Not a scratch.

586
00:49:53,397 --> 00:49:56,223
Is this a student you were going
to send up for a wash-out ride?

587
00:49:56,887 --> 00:49:58,426
What wash-out ride?

588
00:50:11,937 --> 00:50:14,883
That's Navy stuff.
Dunking the last guy to solo.

589
00:50:14,908 --> 00:50:18,242
I never heard of them doing it down here.
- Course you didn't. I just made it up.

590
00:50:19,243 --> 00:50:20,243
Scrap this.

591
00:50:36,908 --> 00:50:39,211
Nice going, Al. Nice going.

592
00:50:39,690 --> 00:50:43,609
That's setting her down on the dime, Al.
- Congratulations, boy. You really did it.

593
00:50:43,633 --> 00:50:46,216
How is Number One?
- Thanks.

594
00:50:46,313 --> 00:50:48,061
They turned the trick.
- Go ahead. Keep him.

595
00:50:48,086 --> 00:50:51,150
That landing was one for the record, Al.
- And they used to call  him "knucklehead."

596
00:50:51,174 --> 00:50:54,033
Yeah!
- Store's closing.

597
00:50:54,058 --> 00:50:56,977
Checking off this reservation to spend
our first weekend in San Antonio.

598
00:50:57,002 --> 00:50:58,703
We're gonna pop all the beer joints.

599
00:50:59,305 --> 00:51:01,594
Oh, gee. I can't go
with you. I got a date.

600
00:51:01,619 --> 00:51:03,588
Oh, gosh. I'm late now.

601
00:51:03,613 --> 00:51:05,783
Go get my suit creased.

602
00:51:06,947 --> 00:51:09,166
Ah, ha ha ha.

603
00:51:11,371 --> 00:51:15,332
Now do you understand
catastrophic instability? - Yes.

604
00:51:15,357 --> 00:51:17,746
Ha ha ha.

605
00:51:25,583 --> 00:51:28,389
Don't forget this war dance
is on me. - We'll settle that later.

606
00:51:28,414 --> 00:51:31,491
Oh, no. I just drew a
month's pay. 75 bucks.

607
00:51:31,516 --> 00:51:33,202
I'm showing you the bright lights.

608
00:51:36,217 --> 00:51:38,758
How many please?
- Two please. - Two?

609
00:51:38,783 --> 00:51:41,137
Si.
- Hey, look.

610
00:51:41,844 --> 00:51:43,809
The center throws
me the ball back.

611
00:51:43,844 --> 00:51:45,682
And I get it and I tuck
it underneath my arm.

612
00:51:45,717 --> 00:51:49,049
Let's break up the whole
thing. - I'm right on your tail.

613
00:51:56,941 --> 00:51:59,667
Well, well. A woman's
work is never done.

614
00:51:59,700 --> 00:52:02,222
What pose is this?
Life-like flying cadet?

615
00:52:02,247 --> 00:52:05,816
Occasionally, I come out of my
darkroom and see Al. - That's fine.

616
00:52:05,841 --> 00:52:08,849
Do you mind if we try to
liven up the party? - Not at all.

617
00:52:08,874 --> 00:52:10,693
Now, waiter.
Two chairs please.

618
00:52:10,718 --> 00:52:12,310
Yes, sir. Coming right up, sir.

619
00:52:12,335 --> 00:52:15,280
Oh, excuse me.
Miss Bartlett, this is Mr. Ludlow.

620
00:52:15,336 --> 00:52:18,132
The hottest pilot in the class.
- How do you do?  - How do you do?

621
00:52:18,414 --> 00:52:20,985
Mr. Cassidy was just telling
me the most fascinating story.

622
00:52:21,010 --> 00:52:22,071
Do go on, Mr. Cassidy.

623
00:52:22,096 --> 00:52:24,797
Oh, yes, about the time he had
the ball on the two-yard line.

624
00:52:24,822 --> 00:52:28,128
Skull fractured. - No. No,
it wasn't a fractured skull.

625
00:52:28,152 --> 00:52:31,533
It was a broken rib.
- Oh, that's right. How silly of me.

626
00:52:34,686 --> 00:52:37,397
Quiet, please.
- You see he's tired.

627
00:52:37,422 --> 00:52:40,959
Irritable. Overworked.
Overexposed.

628
00:52:42,258 --> 00:52:44,924
Look. How about my
having this next dance?

629
00:52:44,959 --> 00:52:47,812
Certainly. If you can find
someone to dance with you.

630
00:52:47,847 --> 00:52:51,317
Ha, ha, ha, ha.
- Oh.

631
00:53:01,869 --> 00:53:08,650
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># I love is hungry for a chance.</b></i></font>

632
00:53:08,675 --> 00:53:10,759
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># Of romance.</b></i></font>

633
00:53:10,784 --> 00:53:15,749
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># For I was born to love.</b></i></font>

634
00:53:15,774 --> 00:53:17,687
They ought to put that
on the menu. - Yeah.

635
00:53:17,712 --> 00:53:21,132
How'd you like to
meet her? - Oh, no.

636
00:53:21,157 --> 00:53:24,437
You just wait here and I'll show you
how it's done. Excuse me.  - Certainly.

637
00:53:24,462 --> 00:53:26,595
Jeff.
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># To be true.</i></b></font>

638
00:53:26,884 --> 00:53:28,884
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># They insist.</b></i></font>

639
00:53:29,548 --> 00:53:36,204
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># For I was born to love.</b></i></font>

640
00:53:38,046 --> 00:53:42,276
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># If I could find just the one I belong.</b></i></font>

641
00:53:42,301 --> 00:53:46,565
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># I would call it a day.</b></i></font>

642
00:53:47,191 --> 00:53:49,785
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># Get him to stay.</b></i></font>

643
00:53:49,810 --> 00:53:53,543
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># And then get older and it's gone.</b></i></font>

644
00:53:53,568 --> 00:53:56,082
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># And gone.</b></i></font>

645
00:53:56,896 --> 00:54:02,677
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># My love would be a lovely thing.</b></i></font>

646
00:54:02,702 --> 00:54:05,263
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># How'd I sing.</b></i></font>

647
00:54:05,288 --> 00:54:12,406
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># For I was born to love.</b></i></font>

648
00:54:21,519 --> 00:54:22,582
Shall we?

649
00:54:23,331 --> 00:54:25,699
Darling, I never
dance with a customer.

650
00:54:28,732 --> 00:54:32,108
If you dance with me, I'll put
you in the Air Corps. - Fine.

651
00:54:32,133 --> 00:54:34,758
I don't think I'm
the type for wings.

652
00:54:35,164 --> 00:54:36,999
Oh, I think so.

653
00:54:41,329 --> 00:54:44,422
Say, who are you?
- Jeff Young.

654
00:54:44,447 --> 00:54:45,969
Now I know you're crazy.

655
00:54:49,329 --> 00:54:53,252
So. It's fourth down. We got
98 yards to go for a touchdown.

656
00:54:53,277 --> 00:54:54,299
Now then.

657
00:54:54,324 --> 00:54:57,885
Should I play safe and kick or
should I take a chance and run?

658
00:55:01,682 --> 00:55:03,940
I said, should I kick or run?

659
00:55:04,346 --> 00:55:05,854
Well, how many men on base?

660
00:55:09,190 --> 00:55:10,502
No.

661
00:55:10,527 --> 00:55:14,457
Strictly speaking, behind that
guy's back, he's kind of conceited.

662
00:55:15,527 --> 00:55:17,027
Yeah, certainly.

663
00:55:21,558 --> 00:55:24,277
Tom, would you like to dance?
- Hmm. Yeah.

664
00:55:24,902 --> 00:55:26,808
Are you really Jefferson Young?

665
00:55:27,652 --> 00:55:29,504
Just Jeff to you please.

666
00:55:29,980 --> 00:55:31,793
You don't look like your pictures.

667
00:55:32,982 --> 00:55:35,951
I'm sorry you're
disappointed. I'm not.

668
00:55:37,239 --> 00:55:39,068
You look just like you should.

669
00:55:39,362 --> 00:55:43,054
Got me all figured out,
haven't you? - Yes, I think so.

670
00:55:43,079 --> 00:55:46,405
Smarter than I am. I never
know what I'm gonna do next.

671
00:55:46,430 --> 00:55:49,515
Oh, Miss Bartlett.
I'd like you to meet Miss uh...?

672
00:55:49,540 --> 00:55:52,994
Vaughn. - Miss Vaughn. - How do you
do? You sang beautifully, miss Vaughn.

673
00:55:53,019 --> 00:55:54,041
Thank you.

674
00:56:03,589 --> 00:56:05,394
Who's that cutting in on your girl?

675
00:56:05,419 --> 00:56:08,746
Oh, that's uh that's Tom Cassidy.

676
00:56:10,723 --> 00:56:14,175
My girl?
Who says she's my girl?

677
00:56:14,200 --> 00:56:16,636
She does.
With her eyes.

678
00:56:17,298 --> 00:56:20,722
Aww. You're way off your course.

679
00:56:31,247 --> 00:56:35,802
My life would be a lovely thing.

680
00:56:37,047 --> 00:56:38,822
How I'd cling.

681
00:56:39,914 --> 00:56:41,937
But I was born to love.

682
00:56:43,015 --> 00:56:45,937
No. Really?

683
00:56:46,681 --> 00:56:50,212
Say, Al. I'd like you
to meet Miss Vaughn.

684
00:56:50,237 --> 00:56:51,962
She was born to love.

685
00:56:54,370 --> 00:56:57,378
Mr. Ludlow.
- How do you do?

686
00:56:57,403 --> 00:57:00,120
You two dance together.
I have to make a separate pass.

687
00:57:04,612 --> 00:57:06,560
Hello, Al.
- Hello, Sally.

688
00:57:06,846 --> 00:57:09,651
Well. That's a warm welcome.

689
00:57:09,676 --> 00:57:12,479
Layoff, Sally.
It started all over down here.

690
00:57:13,236 --> 00:57:16,629
Why'd you follow me for?
- Don't flatter yourself.

691
00:57:16,654 --> 00:57:20,528
I'm down here with the band.
Okay, Al, if that's how it is.

692
00:57:20,553 --> 00:57:23,332
That's how it is.
You messed up my life once.

693
00:57:23,357 --> 00:57:25,764
That's enough.
- Don't worry.

694
00:57:25,789 --> 00:57:29,428
I struggled along without you. I just
hope you find what you're looking for.

695
00:57:35,889 --> 00:57:38,405
Is that really Jeff Young the 3rd?

696
00:57:40,866 --> 00:57:43,397
Don't waste your time, Sally.
He's way out of your league.

697
00:57:46,391 --> 00:57:47,391
Think so?

698
00:58:12,409 --> 00:58:13,737
Is that you, Tom?

699
00:58:15,389 --> 00:58:16,819
Tom, can't make it today.

700
00:58:17,272 --> 00:58:19,796
The average young American is
boning for navigation quiz.

701
00:58:19,821 --> 00:58:22,444
But if I can be of any help,
I'd only be too glad to.

702
00:58:22,469 --> 00:58:24,311
Provided you don't shoot
around the chin.

703
00:58:24,914 --> 00:58:27,032
Thanks. I think I have
about everything I need.

704
00:58:27,057 --> 00:58:29,721
You mean you're finished?
- Mm-hmm. - Then what do you do?

705
00:58:29,746 --> 00:58:33,611
Go home. - Where is that?
- San Antonio. - No kidding? Really?

706
00:58:33,636 --> 00:58:35,619
That's fine. I'll be
over Saturday afternoon.

707
00:58:35,644 --> 00:58:37,735
You'll find me
photographing some bananas.

708
00:58:37,736 --> 00:58:39,582
I'm going to
Guatemala City tomorrow.

709
00:58:39,607 --> 00:58:40,902
Guatemala City?

710
00:58:40,927 --> 00:58:44,949
I wish I'd known you were leaving.
I'd been a little more... well I uh...

711
00:58:45,285 --> 00:58:47,122
Yes?
- Uh.

712
00:58:47,147 --> 00:58:49,802
You got my pictures
yet, young woman?

713
00:58:49,837 --> 00:58:51,707
Yes. They're over here, colonel.

714
00:58:54,238 --> 00:58:56,480
Why don't you
take off in a balloon?

715
00:58:58,974 --> 00:59:02,239
They're excellent.
Creeping up on the enemy.

716
00:59:02,858 --> 00:59:06,755
They won't be dry til
tomorrow. - Well, I can wait.

717
00:59:07,778 --> 00:59:09,653
Oh.
- What's that?

718
00:59:10,249 --> 00:59:12,139
I have to take some negatives out.

719
00:59:13,389 --> 00:59:15,764
Well, be careful.
No light in here.

720
00:59:15,952 --> 00:59:19,936
Hey, ever tell you about the time the
Comanches were surrounding Fort Conner?

721
00:59:19,969 --> 00:59:22,328
No. - I spotted
them in my balloon.

722
00:59:22,353 --> 00:59:24,985
And down I come on
them raining sandbags.

723
00:59:25,321 --> 00:59:29,040
You know, colonel. I hear there's a
full dress review on the parade grounds.

724
00:59:29,075 --> 00:59:31,994
Really? - Mm-hmm. - Well, somebody
ought to tell about these things.

725
00:59:32,019 --> 00:59:35,025
I can't keep a whole
army waiting. - No.

726
00:59:35,050 --> 00:59:36,330
Bye.

727
00:59:45,597 --> 00:59:47,566
Look. Do you have
to go to Guatemala?

728
00:59:48,341 --> 00:59:51,417
Just working girl, you know.
I have to go where they send me.

729
00:59:53,293 --> 00:59:57,052
What's Cassidy doing in
that one? - This one isn't Cassidy.

730
01:00:00,967 --> 01:00:04,803
I don't remember seeing him
around here. - You ought to know him.

731
01:00:04,828 --> 01:00:06,249
You see him everyday.

732
01:00:06,966 --> 01:00:09,680
He's no glamor boy.

733
01:00:09,705 --> 01:00:11,258
His ears are too big.

734
01:00:11,283 --> 01:00:14,156
But he'll make a
magazine cover, just the same.

735
01:00:15,407 --> 01:00:17,150
That's a good face.

736
01:00:17,175 --> 01:00:19,760
A good home-made tough face.

737
01:00:21,158 --> 01:00:22,787
There's a lot of moxie there.

738
01:00:25,169 --> 01:00:26,372
You'll never see this baby

739
01:00:26,397 --> 01:00:29,458
goose-stepping in a colored
shirt with his arm outstretched.

740
01:00:29,685 --> 01:00:32,115
Quite a guy.
What's his name?

741
01:00:33,740 --> 01:00:35,919
Yankee. Joe Yankee.

742
01:00:36,574 --> 01:00:39,257
He's a composite of a lot
of the cadets down here.

743
01:00:40,489 --> 01:00:41,991
They didn't have my chin.

744
01:00:43,052 --> 01:00:46,411
Might be.
- It was a funny thing.

745
01:00:46,436 --> 01:00:49,364
I've got a composite
picture too. A girl.

746
01:00:49,389 --> 01:00:51,950
Miss America.
In the green smock.

747
01:00:51,975 --> 01:00:55,662
Always got her hand in hypo
solution. Knows all the angles.

748
01:00:56,131 --> 01:00:59,264
And waits for the benefits.
- That's rather cute.

749
01:01:00,481 --> 01:01:01,692
Can I kiss you?

750
01:01:03,082 --> 01:01:04,567
Mm-hmm.
- Mmm.

751
01:01:09,621 --> 01:01:13,166
Oh, darn. And every time I try to have
a good time in this Army, a bell rings.

752
01:01:13,916 --> 01:01:14,916
Grr.

753
01:01:16,119 --> 01:01:19,299
Ohh.
- Well, I...

754
01:01:25,817 --> 01:01:28,857
Say, that's fine, Mercer.
Congratulations. - Thanks.

755
01:01:28,969 --> 01:01:32,028
I'm turning my students over
to you. You know most of them.

756
01:01:32,278 --> 01:01:34,380
Ludlow.
Wilcox.

757
01:01:34,405 --> 01:01:36,521
Young.
Front and center.

758
01:01:37,989 --> 01:01:41,100
Lt. Hopkins is going to be
your flying instructor from now on.

759
01:01:41,125 --> 01:01:42,723
I didn't know you
were leaving us, sir.

760
01:01:42,724 --> 01:01:44,320
He's just been named
Flight Commander.

761
01:01:44,344 --> 01:01:47,265
Congratulations, sir. - Thank you.
- We'll miss you, sir.  - Thanks.

762
01:01:47,266 --> 01:01:51,244
Congratulations. - Thank you.
Cassidy and Masters are still upstairs.

763
01:01:51,269 --> 01:01:52,963
They'll probably be in in a minute.

764
01:02:07,380 --> 01:02:08,419
Hey, look out!

765
01:02:14,752 --> 01:02:15,752
Get down.

766
01:02:43,222 --> 01:02:45,497
Get out of there. Clear
the ship before it explodes.

767
01:02:45,521 --> 01:02:48,097
Get going. Come on,
you men in that trash truck.

768
01:02:49,503 --> 01:02:53,253
Bring those extinguishers in here.
What do you think killed the motor?

769
01:02:54,682 --> 01:02:57,665
Cover the gas tank.
Here's another gas tank.

770
01:02:58,986 --> 01:03:01,290
Easy, fellas.
- Let him rest.

771
01:03:06,495 --> 01:03:09,706
Are you coming around?
You're okay, buddy. Take it easy.

772
01:03:10,341 --> 01:03:12,550
I'm sorry.
- It's all right, man.

773
01:03:13,351 --> 01:03:15,660
Sorry. - Sorry for what?
For avoiding a collision?

774
01:03:15,733 --> 01:03:17,544
For saving another man's life?

775
01:03:20,130 --> 01:03:22,654
How about you? Are you all right?
- My hand's just a little burned.

776
01:03:22,726 --> 01:03:26,157
Young. Take Ludlow over to the hospital.
Have them take care of those hands.

777
01:03:26,381 --> 01:03:29,069
Thanks.
- I'm all right.

778
01:03:29,824 --> 01:03:31,186
All right. Come on.

779
01:03:32,253 --> 01:03:35,875
Oh, nothing very serious. They'll
be all right  in a couple of days.

780
01:03:38,190 --> 01:03:39,400
Go ahead. Say it.

781
01:03:40,345 --> 01:03:42,814
You know I let you pull
Masters out alone. They all know it.

782
01:03:43,806 --> 01:03:47,126
Now what are you talking
about? I just got there first.

783
01:03:47,151 --> 01:03:50,720
Sure. You just got there first.

784
01:04:13,568 --> 01:04:16,522
Couldn't find him. - He came
back here for about five minutes.

785
01:04:16,546 --> 01:04:19,849
Changed into his civilian clothes.
And left. - Did he say anything?

786
01:04:19,874 --> 01:04:21,930
Yeah. It doesn't
make sense though.

787
01:04:21,954 --> 01:04:23,773
I hand him a couple
letters from Guatemala.

788
01:04:23,798 --> 01:04:25,952
Addressed to Jeff Young
the 3rd just as plain as day.

789
01:04:25,977 --> 01:04:27,860
So he says he isn't the guy
that they were written to.

790
01:04:27,884 --> 01:04:30,084
And he tears them up and
throws them in the wastebasket.

791
01:04:30,182 --> 01:04:31,798
You didn't save me the stamps.

792
01:04:37,415 --> 01:04:38,415
Come on.

793
01:04:39,831 --> 01:04:41,097
Get me your laundry.

794
01:04:58,862 --> 01:04:59,965
All present.

795
01:05:01,903 --> 01:05:02,903
Good night.

796
01:05:14,096 --> 01:05:16,846
Where do you think
you're going? - Into town.

797
01:05:18,447 --> 01:05:21,440
Don't be a dolt. Why
stick your neck out too?

798
01:05:21,465 --> 01:05:24,207
I got to find him.
That guy's in a real storm.

799
01:05:25,440 --> 01:05:32,216
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># My love would be a lovely thing.</b></i></font>

800
01:05:32,255 --> 01:05:34,747
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># Promising.</b></i></font>

801
01:05:34,772 --> 01:05:42,772
<font color=#00FF80><b><i># For I was born to love.</b></i></font>

802
01:05:53,054 --> 01:05:54,077
Hello.

803
01:05:56,176 --> 01:05:57,176
That.

804
01:05:57,704 --> 01:06:01,680
Now I know why I came down
here. - What took you so long?

805
01:06:02,305 --> 01:06:06,759
I was trying to be a flier.

806
01:06:06,784 --> 01:06:09,673
But you won't be if they catch
you down here on a weekday night.

807
01:06:09,698 --> 01:06:13,569
Eh, let 'em catch me.
I'm through.

808
01:06:14,655 --> 01:06:18,191
I'm no Joe Yankee.
- Who?

809
01:06:19,011 --> 01:06:21,190
If I want to fly, I'll buy a blimp.

810
01:06:23,683 --> 01:06:26,938
You can buy anything
you want. - Yeah.

811
01:06:28,895 --> 01:06:30,348
Anything but wings.

812
01:06:36,465 --> 01:06:39,662
Look. Stick with
me tonight, will you?

813
01:06:40,749 --> 01:06:41,983
Don't leave me alone.

814
01:06:43,696 --> 01:06:46,030
Come on.
Let's get out of here.

815
01:06:54,217 --> 01:06:57,180
Johnnie, tell the boss I'm
leaving early tonight. - Yes, ma'am.

816
01:07:25,961 --> 01:07:29,728
Well. Isn't it kind of late for
you to go around ringing doorbells?

817
01:07:30,009 --> 01:07:33,845
They told me at the Colonnade,
Jeff is with you. - Eh.

818
01:07:33,870 --> 01:07:35,986
Well, if it isn't old Al.

819
01:07:36,011 --> 01:07:38,487
Take a seat, cadet. Take a seat.

820
01:07:38,745 --> 01:07:40,456
Have anything on the house.

821
01:07:40,807 --> 01:07:42,901
Nothing's too good for a hero.

822
01:07:44,331 --> 01:07:47,566
Joe Yankee.
The hero of the day.

823
01:07:47,607 --> 01:07:50,692
Or will it be wave my
hanky, wave, wave, wave?

824
01:07:55,702 --> 01:07:57,899
Ever hear of Joe Yankee?

825
01:07:58,902 --> 01:08:03,710
He's kind of a cross between
Sir Galahad and and Daniel Boone.

826
01:08:05,173 --> 01:08:08,852
He's full of moxie.
- We'll talk about that tomorrow.

827
01:08:08,877 --> 01:08:11,899
Right now, you're going
back with me. - Oh, no, I'm not.

828
01:08:12,914 --> 01:08:15,516
Sally and I are taking
a little trip tomorrow.

829
01:08:16,351 --> 01:08:18,534
She isn't looking for Joe again.

830
01:08:18,559 --> 01:08:21,909
Jeff Young is good enough
for her. - Plenty good enough.

831
01:08:21,934 --> 01:08:23,073
Yes.

832
01:08:24,351 --> 01:08:27,266
New Orleans.
Sun Valley. Mexico City.

833
01:08:27,291 --> 01:08:29,406
That's it. Mexico City.

834
01:08:30,164 --> 01:08:32,328
See the world while it's still here.

835
01:08:36,381 --> 01:08:39,060
Sal.
Here's to us.

836
01:08:46,490 --> 01:08:47,490
Ice.

837
01:08:51,990 --> 01:08:53,273
For my drink.

838
01:08:54,365 --> 01:08:55,859
Not my head.

839
01:09:07,561 --> 01:09:08,741
Lay off him.

840
01:09:08,766 --> 01:09:12,672
You're getting what you want
down here.- You want his dough.

841
01:09:12,697 --> 01:09:14,586
I couldn't be on the level, could I?

842
01:09:15,423 --> 01:09:18,781
You never were with me.
Tell him to go back to the field.

843
01:09:18,806 --> 01:09:20,672
You must think I'm crazy.

844
01:09:21,216 --> 01:09:24,982
I'm always wanted to
go to Mexico. - Listen.

845
01:09:25,050 --> 01:09:28,337
How long do you think it
would last? Jeff's no dope.

846
01:09:28,362 --> 01:09:30,831
What happens when he
sobers up and find you there?

847
01:09:30,856 --> 01:09:33,183
A cheap little gyp
with her hooks in him.

848
01:09:36,066 --> 01:09:38,306
You tried that once before
and got into a lot of trouble.

849
01:09:39,097 --> 01:09:42,332
Now tell him to go back to
the field or I'll spill. - Just try it.

850
01:09:45,636 --> 01:09:48,097
Colder than a well digger's ice box.

851
01:09:52,277 --> 01:09:54,360
Jeff.
- Have some flask.

852
01:09:58,562 --> 01:10:00,522
Let's dance.
- Jeff.

853
01:10:00,547 --> 01:10:03,209
You better run along before
you get any more trouble.

854
01:10:03,234 --> 01:10:06,905
Why don't ice cubes come
in single packs instead of in litters?

855
01:10:06,930 --> 01:10:09,445
Jeff, did you hear me?
- Yes, I heard you.

856
01:10:09,470 --> 01:10:13,430
We're taking off for Mexico. And
planes don't leave from Randolph.

857
01:10:13,883 --> 01:10:15,797
Let's wait until you can fly me there.

858
01:10:15,822 --> 01:10:18,486
I'm no flier. That's Al's department.

859
01:10:18,511 --> 01:10:21,425
He's got it. And I haven't.
- Don't make me laugh.

860
01:10:21,450 --> 01:10:24,050
Come on. It's getting
pretty late. - Oh.

861
01:10:25,762 --> 01:10:28,105
So you're running
out on me, huh?

862
01:10:29,120 --> 01:10:32,121
You're one of these
hot and cold propositions.

863
01:10:32,170 --> 01:10:36,054
I'm not running out on you,
Jeff, honey. I'll be waiting around.

864
01:10:36,479 --> 01:10:39,583
I can tell you really don't want to
break away now. You wouldn't be happy.

865
01:10:40,772 --> 01:10:41,772
Uh.

866
01:10:45,264 --> 01:10:47,842
Well.
Maybe you're right.

867
01:10:50,360 --> 01:10:52,219
You're a good kid, Sal.

868
01:10:53,984 --> 01:10:57,016
You're all right. - Come
on. Let's run along now.

869
01:10:59,376 --> 01:11:02,369
You gonna call me in
the morning? - I promise I will.

870
01:11:02,394 --> 01:11:04,112
Early?
- Early.

871
01:11:05,159 --> 01:11:06,361
All right.

872
01:11:22,439 --> 01:11:23,767
Good night, Jeff.

873
01:11:31,877 --> 01:11:33,361
That was smart, Sally.

874
01:11:33,386 --> 01:11:36,651
Not you or your whole Army
can take him away from me.

875
01:11:37,268 --> 01:11:39,596
And don't you forget it.

876
01:11:43,749 --> 01:11:46,053
Nice kid, huh?
- Yeah.

877
01:11:46,078 --> 01:11:48,649
Wipe the paint off
your puss. - Really?

878
01:11:54,186 --> 01:11:55,186
Hmm.

879
01:12:02,219 --> 01:12:05,978
Kelly Field, here we come. The
finest food in the Army for four miles.

880
01:12:06,011 --> 01:12:08,181
Maning. - Oh, forget
the food, knucklehead.

881
01:12:08,206 --> 01:12:10,455
Capt. Mercer never
did like your snap rolls.

882
01:12:10,480 --> 01:12:13,822
Well, he wouldn't wash us out in a
final check. He taught us all we know.

883
01:12:13,847 --> 01:12:16,667
Don't let Hopkins hears
you say that. Just think, Al.

884
01:12:16,692 --> 01:12:20,620
The fastest ships, cross
countries, night flying. - Yeah.

885
01:12:20,880 --> 01:12:23,395
And a pair of wings.
- Aw, this is going to be a cinch.

886
01:12:23,420 --> 01:12:25,036
We're practically at Kelly now.

887
01:12:27,591 --> 01:12:29,825
Flying Cadet Young,
reporting for final check, sir.

888
01:12:56,986 --> 01:12:58,877
What do we do, sit this one out?

889
01:13:22,919 --> 01:13:26,326
Climb on to traffic to
2.000 feet into a practice area.

890
01:13:26,351 --> 01:13:28,951
Show me gentle,
medium and speed banks.

891
01:14:13,678 --> 01:14:15,560
Putrid. Putrid.

892
01:14:17,514 --> 01:14:20,776
Alright. Alright.
Show me some slow rolls.

893
01:14:54,407 --> 01:14:57,603
How did I ever get
myself a job like this?

894
01:14:58,483 --> 01:15:00,893
I can't stand
anymore. Take me home.

895
01:15:12,363 --> 01:15:16,120
Raunchy. Very raunchy. I hate
the pass you men on those rides.

896
01:15:16,145 --> 01:15:18,292
But we have to
get somebody to Kelly.

897
01:15:44,218 --> 01:15:45,925
By the way.

898
01:15:47,286 --> 01:15:50,247
The next job you take, young
lady, better be close to home.

899
01:15:50,272 --> 01:15:53,161
Like photographing
the San Antonio Water Works.

900
01:15:53,458 --> 01:15:55,466
You miss me?
- Missed you?

901
01:15:55,981 --> 01:15:57,693
The day they turned me
loose on cross-country,

902
01:15:57,717 --> 01:15:59,880
I almost made it
non-stop to Guatemala.

903
01:16:02,067 --> 01:16:05,771
Why'd you turn back?
It's rather lonely down there.

904
01:16:05,803 --> 01:16:08,162
Oh. Mr. Camera must be slipping.

905
01:16:08,725 --> 01:16:11,053
I thought he kept
you too busy to be lonely.

906
01:16:11,912 --> 01:16:14,373
Maybe my mind
wasn't on my work.

907
01:16:17,219 --> 01:16:19,501
Let's finish this dance
from the terrace.

908
01:16:21,415 --> 01:16:23,063
Hey, Jeff. You're wanted
on the horn. - What?

909
01:16:23,088 --> 01:16:26,440
Telephone call for you. - Well, tear
it up. I'm not taking any calls tonight.

910
01:16:26,465 --> 01:16:27,465
Jeff.

911
01:16:28,471 --> 01:16:30,346
You'd better take this one.

912
01:16:31,369 --> 01:16:35,238
Oh. I'm sorry, Cally.
Will you excuse me?

913
01:16:35,263 --> 01:16:36,387
Yes, certainly.

914
01:16:43,840 --> 01:16:46,551
You know Mr. Cassidy. You're
wasting your time in the Air Corps.

915
01:16:46,576 --> 01:16:49,965
There's a distinguished career waiting
for you in the diplomatic service.

916
01:16:49,990 --> 01:16:51,652
Yeah?

917
01:16:59,419 --> 01:17:02,177
Hello.
- Hello, Jeff.

918
01:17:02,202 --> 01:17:04,983
Why haven't you called?
- Well, I was busy.

919
01:17:05,008 --> 01:17:08,614
Well, you can't be so busy. I hear
there's a dance out there tonight.

920
01:17:08,641 --> 01:17:11,358
It's just a small party.
Our last night at Randolph.

921
01:17:11,624 --> 01:17:13,171
I can get away early.

922
01:17:13,196 --> 01:17:16,032
I think I'll drive up for a while.

923
01:17:16,704 --> 01:17:18,298
I wouldn't do that, Sally.

924
01:17:19,706 --> 01:17:22,559
Why, Jeff, it's been
weeks since I've seen you.

925
01:17:28,815 --> 01:17:31,504
Now Sally, I thought
we've been all through this.

926
01:17:31,982 --> 01:17:34,793
I thought you were going to be
intelligent about it. - What does that mean?

927
01:17:34,818 --> 01:17:36,223
Goodbye. Good luck.
We've had our fun.

928
01:17:36,248 --> 01:17:39,621
You go your way. I'll go mine.
Don't try and sell me that routine, Jeff.

929
01:17:40,079 --> 01:17:43,474
I wish I could think of a
better ending but I can't. - No?

930
01:17:43,499 --> 01:17:46,608
Maybe I can. I want
to see you tonight.

931
01:17:47,042 --> 01:17:49,654
Sorry, I made other plans.
- Listen, Mister Jeff Young.

932
01:17:49,679 --> 01:17:51,413
You drop up to my
place after that dance.

933
01:17:51,438 --> 01:17:53,375
Or I'll start making
a few plans of my own.

934
01:17:54,210 --> 01:17:55,851
I'm expecting you.

935
01:18:19,020 --> 01:18:21,395
Attention. Orders.
Headquarters.

936
01:18:21,420 --> 01:18:23,935
Flying Cadet Detachment.
The Air Corps Primary Flying School.

937
01:18:23,959 --> 01:18:26,575
Office of the Commandant.
Randolph Field, Texas.

938
01:18:26,600 --> 01:18:28,559
Detachment order.
Order Number Ten.

939
01:18:28,879 --> 01:18:30,820
All existing appointments
of flying cadets

940
01:18:30,821 --> 01:18:32,895
as officers and
non-commissioned officers

941
01:18:32,920 --> 01:18:35,004
in the Flying Cadet
Battalion are revoked.

942
01:18:35,382 --> 01:18:36,942
And the following
appointments are announced.

943
01:18:37,469 --> 01:18:40,190
Effective upon departure
to Kelly Field at 9 a. m. tomorrow.

944
01:18:40,609 --> 01:18:44,439
To be Senior Cadet Captain,
Flying Cadet Ludlow, A.H.

945
01:18:47,509 --> 01:18:49,279
Congratulations, Ludlow.

946
01:18:49,876 --> 01:18:51,994
Al, they picked a
good man this time.

947
01:18:52,029 --> 01:18:52,853
Yeah, but he was just
getting to be a good guy.

948
01:18:52,877 --> 01:18:54,368
Now he has to
start playing grandma.

949
01:18:57,697 --> 01:19:00,184
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>KELLY FIELD</b></font>

950
01:20:46,911 --> 01:20:50,864
A very stylish landing, mister.
- You know it's funny.

951
01:20:51,341 --> 01:20:53,770
When I came down, I
wasn't even looking at the field.

952
01:20:55,139 --> 01:20:57,311
Think I can get a job
around here the beacon?

953
01:20:57,336 --> 01:21:01,171
I have a better idea.
Tell me something, Miss Bartlett.

954
01:21:01,195 --> 01:21:04,677
Yes. - How is it nobody
ever married you before I will?

955
01:21:06,355 --> 01:21:07,445
I don't know.

956
01:21:09,779 --> 01:21:12,703
I suppose it's because of the funny
kind of life I've made for myself.

957
01:21:13,245 --> 01:21:16,892
I think really it's because nobody
has to make me want to give it up.

958
01:21:18,598 --> 01:21:20,204
Could you give it up for me?

959
01:21:21,158 --> 01:21:22,752
I know I could if.

960
01:21:23,577 --> 01:21:25,530
You were just Lt. Young.

961
01:21:27,243 --> 01:21:29,491
Not Jefferson Young the 3rd.

962
01:21:31,294 --> 01:21:35,134
Gee, I'd have to live your
way. Can you wait for me?

963
01:21:36,790 --> 01:21:38,773
I think it frightens me just a bit.

964
01:21:40,242 --> 01:21:42,020
Well, don't worry.

965
01:21:42,587 --> 01:21:45,577
After I get my wings, I'm
not going back to Long Island.

966
01:21:45,602 --> 01:21:49,554
Wall Street. And those
tired coming-out parties.

967
01:21:50,462 --> 01:21:53,751
I'm staying with the
Air Corps. For good.

968
01:21:54,142 --> 01:21:55,251
Well.

969
01:21:56,270 --> 01:21:57,774
I guess I am too.

970
01:22:21,058 --> 01:22:22,058
Ho hum.

971
01:22:28,682 --> 01:22:31,839
Good night, darling.
- Good night. Hey, wait a minute.

972
01:22:43,301 --> 01:22:46,387
You shouldn't be out here this
late, Sally. It's against regulations.

973
01:22:46,544 --> 01:22:50,067
I can tell them about a few
regulations you've broken, Mr. Young.

974
01:22:50,682 --> 01:22:52,373
Get in.
- Never mind that.

975
01:22:52,662 --> 01:22:56,405
Sally, you and I are through.
Our account is closed.

976
01:22:58,869 --> 01:22:59,869
Is it?

977
01:23:13,418 --> 01:23:16,535
Oh, come on, Grandma. Button
on your bust and let's get going.

978
01:23:16,560 --> 01:23:18,857
On the double, old lady.
Come on. - All right. Bye, boys.

979
01:23:18,882 --> 01:23:21,411
Just don't let me lose you in
the turns. That's all. - Ho ho.

980
01:23:21,436 --> 01:23:23,818
A skipper from Randolph.
- Yeah, Capt. Mercer.

981
01:23:31,741 --> 01:23:34,461
Well, hello. - Certainly
glad to see you, sir.

982
01:23:34,486 --> 01:23:36,705
Oh, you've been laying
for me, huh? - No, sir.

983
01:23:36,730 --> 01:23:38,360
You weren't as
tough as all that.

984
01:23:38,361 --> 01:23:40,614
Well, I see all three
of you are still here.

985
01:23:40,615 --> 01:23:43,666
Yes, we're still here.
We proved that flying is safe.

986
01:23:43,691 --> 01:23:47,221
I guess you have at that.
- Are you transferred over here, sir?

987
01:23:47,246 --> 01:23:48,971
No, just over here on business.

988
01:23:49,287 --> 01:23:53,761
I've been assigned to a Flying Fortress
Squadron next month out at Marsh Field.

989
01:23:54,082 --> 01:23:57,699
You know. I'd like to
have you men in my outfit.

990
01:23:57,724 --> 01:23:59,396
If you're assigned to Bombardment.

991
01:23:59,421 --> 01:24:02,177
That's where we really
separate the men from the boys.

992
01:24:02,202 --> 01:24:05,021
Well, that lets Cassidy out.
- As you were, chump.

993
01:24:06,607 --> 01:24:11,399
You know how glad I am to see
you three finishing the course.

994
01:24:11,424 --> 01:24:13,628
I'd like to give you one
more piece of advice.

995
01:24:14,247 --> 01:24:17,034
You're at the peak
right now. Hot pilots.

996
01:24:17,647 --> 01:24:19,987
Out in the service,
you will run into older pilots.

997
01:24:20,012 --> 01:24:22,643
Old fuds like me that
aren't what they used to be.

998
01:24:23,381 --> 01:24:27,278
You can fly rings around
them. But have a heart, boys.

999
01:24:27,929 --> 01:24:29,793
Break the news to them gently.

1000
01:24:34,860 --> 01:24:38,776
What's an "old fud"? - That's what
Grandma's going to grow up to be.

1001
01:24:44,149 --> 01:24:46,165
One more week and I'm
second lieutenant with wings.

1002
01:24:46,190 --> 01:24:49,667
45 minutes of safe and sane flying
behind Grandma here and we're through.

1003
01:24:49,917 --> 01:24:52,105
You do you want me to do,
dive on the colonel's quarters?

1004
01:24:52,129 --> 01:24:53,612
Oh, no. We wouldn't think of it.

1005
01:24:56,124 --> 01:24:59,444
What, hop a hedge? Why,
that's against the Scout's code.

1006
01:24:59,827 --> 01:25:03,485
Grandma, huh? All right.
I'll give you guys a workout.

1007
01:28:34,061 --> 01:28:38,342
Now they'll wash me out
for this, won't they, Jeff?

1008
01:29:06,699 --> 01:29:08,589
What sort of a
racket is this anyway?

1009
01:29:09,386 --> 01:29:12,027
Graduation Day and they throw
out the best man on the class.

1010
01:29:12,177 --> 01:29:14,404
For something he was
no more responsible for than I.

1011
01:29:14,794 --> 01:29:16,568
Just because you were the leader.

1012
01:29:17,255 --> 01:29:19,325
Everybody hedgehops once in awhile.

1013
01:29:21,076 --> 01:29:22,302
We egged you into it.

1014
01:29:23,598 --> 01:29:25,545
Tom happened to be
the one who slipped up.

1015
01:29:27,805 --> 01:29:31,558
I am responsible. - If you listened to
me, we could have cooked up a story.

1016
01:29:33,095 --> 01:29:35,546
Don't you think I felt bad
enough about lying out of it?

1017
01:29:35,571 --> 01:29:38,023
And you didn't do me any good
when you horned in on the blame.

1018
01:29:38,048 --> 01:29:40,148
Almost got yourself washed out too.

1019
01:29:41,235 --> 01:29:43,232
So what's the difference?

1020
01:29:43,917 --> 01:29:47,626
I'm quitting anyway. Fed
up with their kind of discipline.

1021
01:29:48,227 --> 01:29:50,627
They can have it and take a
running full-twist into the lake.

1022
01:29:51,038 --> 01:29:52,391
Aw, cool off.

1023
01:29:53,320 --> 01:29:57,439
You'll feel better after they
pin those wings on you. - Wings?

1024
01:29:58,121 --> 01:30:00,335
I'll hang 'em in my trophy room.

1025
01:30:02,076 --> 01:30:05,283
Where do you get off,
talking like this? You got no beef.

1026
01:30:05,308 --> 01:30:08,386
You came down here polo-playing
drip. And they made a flier on you.

1027
01:30:10,636 --> 01:30:12,128
I'm sorry, Jeff.

1028
01:30:17,571 --> 01:30:21,177
Look, Jeff. You're the
best friend I've ever had.

1029
01:30:22,349 --> 01:30:24,427
I just don't want to
see you go off your nut.

1030
01:30:32,915 --> 01:30:35,503
I'm washed up. Sure.

1031
01:30:35,538 --> 01:30:37,591
Just wasn't in the cards for me.

1032
01:30:38,705 --> 01:30:41,158
We both want something
when we came down here.

1033
01:30:41,436 --> 01:30:43,589
We both felt the same way.

1034
01:30:44,179 --> 01:30:47,061
And if I'm not in the Air Corps,
I want to know that you're in.

1035
01:30:47,100 --> 01:30:49,325
But you got the
thing we both wanted.

1036
01:30:49,937 --> 01:30:52,172
And you earned it.
The hard way.

1037
01:30:52,781 --> 01:30:55,222
That's something
your money won't buy.

1038
01:30:56,872 --> 01:31:00,148
Something bigger than you or me.

1039
01:31:05,502 --> 01:31:06,627
Stick with it. Jeff.

1040
01:31:11,050 --> 01:31:13,471
Come on. Get going.
You got to fly that review.

1041
01:31:15,049 --> 01:31:16,236
See you later.

1042
01:31:54,164 --> 01:31:55,860
Al. Wait.

1043
01:31:59,283 --> 01:32:01,939
Al. You can't go like this.

1044
01:32:01,980 --> 01:32:04,486
Ah, the more speed,
the better the takeoff.

1045
01:32:04,675 --> 01:32:07,918
Jeff and I have plans
for you. - Well, thanks.

1046
01:32:07,943 --> 01:32:09,394
I'd rather be on my own.

1047
01:32:12,168 --> 01:32:13,168
Where are you going?

1048
01:32:14,450 --> 01:32:18,271
It's a big country. Tell Jeff so
long and to stay on the beam.

1049
01:32:18,768 --> 01:32:19,997
He'll know what I mean.

1050
01:32:25,284 --> 01:32:26,550
It's from both of us.

1051
01:32:30,471 --> 01:32:34,168
Thanks. - How many
aviators do you kiss, sister?

1052
01:32:34,193 --> 01:32:36,184
Sally, stop it.
- Try and make it.

1053
01:32:36,209 --> 01:32:37,817
I know. I read
about you and Jeff.

1054
01:32:37,842 --> 01:32:40,410
A big military wedding
for a dress affair.

1055
01:32:40,435 --> 01:32:42,271
Now you don't want to go
out there, Sally. - Oh, don't I?

1056
01:32:42,296 --> 01:32:45,925
I'm tired of being pushed around.
So they're giving him his wings?

1057
01:32:45,960 --> 01:32:47,779
They won't dare
when I get through.

1058
01:32:47,814 --> 01:32:49,563
I'll give them a scandal
that'll shake the Army.

1059
01:32:49,598 --> 01:32:52,640
I'll tell 'em a bedtime story
they won't forget. - Al, let her go.

1060
01:32:52,665 --> 01:32:55,960
Jeff hasn't seen her in
months. - That's your story.

1061
01:32:55,985 --> 01:32:59,759
He's seen me lots of times.
How do you think I got his car?

1062
01:32:59,784 --> 01:33:01,017
Let go of me.

1063
01:33:01,042 --> 01:33:03,979
Jeff Young can't pick me up and drop
me without seeing where I'm gonna land.

1064
01:33:04,003 --> 01:33:06,574
I'll make him marry me.
- Sally, be sensible.

1065
01:33:06,609 --> 01:33:08,866
You can't make anybody
marry you. - Can't I?

1066
01:33:08,901 --> 01:33:10,958
Who do you think
I am, Snow White?

1067
01:33:12,042 --> 01:33:13,317
I'm in trouble.

1068
01:33:34,505 --> 01:33:36,833
Jeff gave you kind of
a rotten deal, didn't he?

1069
01:33:37,314 --> 01:33:40,622
I'll say he did.
But I'll make him squirm.

1070
01:33:40,647 --> 01:33:42,716
I'll take care of that pal of yours.

1071
01:33:44,124 --> 01:33:48,093
He's no pal of mine. Not after
the way he kicked you around.

1072
01:33:48,820 --> 01:33:50,655
Well, I'm through
being kicked around.

1073
01:33:53,388 --> 01:33:55,266
I don't know
what's the matter with me.

1074
01:33:56,107 --> 01:33:57,805
I don't want to hurt anybody.

1075
01:33:58,977 --> 01:34:00,549
But they're always hurting me.

1076
01:34:01,565 --> 01:34:04,619
Look, Sally. Jeff's got
another half-hour in the air.

1077
01:34:05,629 --> 01:34:07,963
No sense starting anything
till you had a talk with him.

1078
01:34:08,551 --> 01:34:11,223
I think you need a
drink. - I'll say I do.

1079
01:34:12,232 --> 01:34:13,856
Might be able to fix something up.

1080
01:34:16,947 --> 01:34:18,416
Why aren't you up there?

1081
01:34:20,267 --> 01:34:21,447
They washed me out.

1082
01:34:23,926 --> 01:34:26,908
Wouldn't you know it.
The same old Al.

1083
01:34:26,933 --> 01:34:29,050
You and me both make a couple of -

1084
01:34:30,022 --> 01:34:31,527
also-rans.

1085
01:34:33,008 --> 01:34:35,183
Come on, Al. I need that drink.

1086
01:35:40,933 --> 01:35:43,106
Going up? - Not yet,
but I will be in 10 minutes.

1087
01:35:43,130 --> 01:35:45,172
This came for you, sir.
- Oh, thanks.

1088
01:35:51,381 --> 01:35:53,108
<font color=#C28585><b>LT JEFF YOUNG
KELLY FIELD TEX</b></font>

1089
01:35:53,603 --> 01:35:55,261
<font color=#C28585><b>TAKING SALLY AWAY.
WE ARE GETTING MARRIED
AL</b></font>

1090
01:36:00,518 --> 01:36:02,644
Where's Miss Bartlett?
- Back at home.

1091
01:36:02,669 --> 01:36:04,909
Well, if you see her first,
tell her I'm looking for her.

1092
01:36:17,347 --> 01:36:19,956
Oh, there you are. I've
been looking all over for you.

1093
01:36:36,471 --> 01:36:39,074
Carolyn. Al's gone.
I just got this.

1094
01:36:42,684 --> 01:36:45,364
Oh, no. - What made
him do a thing like that?

1095
01:36:47,099 --> 01:36:49,834
Can't you imagine?
- No, I can't. I had no idea...

1096
01:36:49,859 --> 01:36:52,250
Jeff. Have you been seeing Sally?

1097
01:36:54,928 --> 01:36:56,421
Yes, I have.

1098
01:36:57,666 --> 01:37:01,392
She threatened to go to the commandant.
I wanted my wings so... I saw her.

1099
01:37:02,285 --> 01:37:03,736
I gave her a check.

1100
01:37:04,237 --> 01:37:06,331
Do you think that
takes care of everything?

1101
01:37:06,356 --> 01:37:08,237
What did you expect me to do?

1102
01:37:08,541 --> 01:37:11,347
Jeff, one can't use a
checkbook for a conscience.

1103
01:37:11,382 --> 01:37:13,255
What's that got
to do with us? - A lot.

1104
01:37:13,290 --> 01:37:16,262
I've had a swell
time on my own, Jeff.

1105
01:37:16,613 --> 01:37:19,389
I've got to know what I'm giving
it up for. - Look. Just because Sally...

1106
01:37:19,414 --> 01:37:21,210
She was here this afternoon.

1107
01:37:21,476 --> 01:37:25,328
I spoke to her. And so
did Al. - What did she say?

1108
01:37:28,042 --> 01:37:29,786
Don't you know?

1109
01:37:31,556 --> 01:37:33,725
Al drove away with her.

1110
01:37:34,260 --> 01:37:36,806
You wouldn't be getting your
wings today if it weren't for him.

1111
01:37:37,111 --> 01:37:39,212
A pleasant thought, isn't it?

1112
01:37:44,138 --> 01:37:46,591
Jeff, I wonder if you're
worth what he did for you.

1113
01:37:48,749 --> 01:37:50,013
No, I'm not.

1114
01:37:59,621 --> 01:38:01,129
Lawrence, P.T.

1115
01:38:05,910 --> 01:38:08,638
Thank you, sir. - Congratulations.
Mr. Lawrence. - Thank you, sir.

1116
01:38:09,388 --> 01:38:10,998
Wilcox, D.A.

1117
01:38:16,576 --> 01:38:19,021
Congratulations. Mr. Wilcox.
- Thank you, sir.

1118
01:38:20,099 --> 01:38:21,607
Young, J.

1119
01:38:26,544 --> 01:38:29,335
Congratulations, Mr. Young.
- Thank you, sir.

1120
01:38:30,757 --> 01:38:32,280
Arden, M.

1121
01:38:36,968 --> 01:38:39,131
Congratulations, Mr. Young.
- Thank you, sir.

1122
01:38:39,132 --> 01:38:41,030
Congratulations, Mr. Arden.
- Thank you, sir.

1123
01:38:42,679 --> 01:38:44,288
Rutherford, D.

1124
01:38:47,141 --> 01:38:49,218
Quinn, A.J.

1125
01:39:00,234 --> 01:39:01,698
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>KANSAS CITY</b></font>

1126
01:39:04,228 --> 01:39:05,759
Why, Mr. Vanessa.

1127
01:39:05,784 --> 01:39:08,775
And me, a respectable
married woman for six months.

1128
01:39:09,691 --> 01:39:10,901
Sure, I like it.

1129
01:39:10,926 --> 01:39:14,706
I'm up to my elbows in diamonds
and down to my knees in silver fox.

1130
01:39:18,374 --> 01:39:22,083
Cut the clowning, Tony. Haven't
you got a spot for me at the Paradise?

1131
01:39:23,536 --> 01:39:26,645
I don't wanna trip to
Florida. I want a job.

1132
01:39:29,700 --> 01:39:32,686
I know. They got
big oranges in, Florida.

1133
01:39:34,584 --> 01:39:37,437
Un-uh. Doctor told me
to stay in Kansas City.

1134
01:39:37,462 --> 01:39:41,329
Smoke's good for what
I've got. Vanessa.

1135
01:39:41,822 --> 01:39:44,056
Okay, Tony.
Skip it.

1136
01:39:44,081 --> 01:39:47,720
I guess you and I don't think
alike. I'm sorry I bothered you.

1137
01:39:47,745 --> 01:39:51,706
The wolf. He was a nice
kid when he was a barber.

1138
01:39:51,731 --> 01:39:53,980
Czar of the numbers
racket is something else.

1139
01:39:55,191 --> 01:39:56,948
Did you...?
- No, nothing.

1140
01:39:57,561 --> 01:40:01,505
Don't bite my head off. I just wanted
to know how you wanted your eggs.

1141
01:40:03,187 --> 01:40:04,372
Scrambled.

1142
01:40:05,225 --> 01:40:08,186
It would've been a commission
job anyway. - Don't kid me, Al.

1143
01:40:08,211 --> 01:40:10,701
You didn't want that job.
You don't want any job.

1144
01:40:10,726 --> 01:40:13,500
Except flying. - I told you
I was through with flying.

1145
01:40:14,711 --> 01:40:19,213
How about cooking those eggs?
- No, I'm sick of cooking for you.

1146
01:40:19,306 --> 01:40:21,298
I'm sick of this cheap dump.

1147
01:40:21,728 --> 01:40:25,541
I don't have to stay here.
I can skip any time I want to.

1148
01:40:28,317 --> 01:40:30,355
You think the baby's stopping me?

1149
01:40:30,380 --> 01:40:32,891
Well, there isn't any baby.
There never was.

1150
01:40:34,054 --> 01:40:35,395
I knew that, Sally.

1151
01:40:39,622 --> 01:40:41,184
Then what did
you marry me for?

1152
01:40:43,453 --> 01:40:45,065
So you didn't want to help me.

1153
01:40:45,066 --> 01:40:48,233
You didn't care anything
about me. I didn't matter.

1154
01:40:48,426 --> 01:40:50,942
What a sucker I've been.

1155
01:40:50,977 --> 01:40:52,484
Trying to make a go
of a two-cent marriage

1156
01:40:52,509 --> 01:40:55,687
while all the time you're
grandstanding for a guy named Jeff Young.

1157
01:40:57,236 --> 01:40:59,664
It's on me, isn't it, Al?

1158
01:41:27,503 --> 01:41:31,055
<font color=#FFFFFF><b>MARCH FIELD
LAND OF THE
FLYING FORTRESS</b></font>

1159
01:42:56,984 --> 01:42:59,292
Where's the ship we
borrowed from Hamilton Field?

1160
01:42:59,327 --> 01:43:01,437
Over in Hangar 2, sir.
They just pulled her in.

1161
01:43:03,569 --> 01:43:07,148
What about that turbo supercharger
on 32? - Another two hours, sir.

1162
01:43:07,183 --> 01:43:08,611
That's just dandy.

1163
01:43:09,803 --> 01:43:11,978
So they sent us a B-17B, huh?

1164
01:43:13,217 --> 01:43:15,849
How about 32? She
going to be ready on time?

1165
01:43:15,884 --> 01:43:19,047
Not for another two hours at least, sir.
- And all we've got is 20 minutes.

1166
01:43:19,626 --> 01:43:22,348
Good thing we sent to Hamilton
for a spare. We'll have to use it.

1167
01:43:22,373 --> 01:43:24,014
Did she come down with
a full enlisted crew?

1168
01:43:24,038 --> 01:43:25,748
I don't know, sir.
I was just on my way to check.

1169
01:43:25,772 --> 01:43:27,890
We better find out. I want to
go to the crew that came with it.

1170
01:43:27,914 --> 01:43:29,611
You can relieve those men.
- All right, sir.

1171
01:43:29,612 --> 01:43:32,444
All right, sergeant. Tell your men
to knock off. We won't use that ship.

1172
01:43:47,374 --> 01:43:49,639
Crew chief?
- Up front, sir.

1173
01:43:50,724 --> 01:43:53,492
What's the rest of your crew?
- They're getting something to eat, sir.

1174
01:43:53,516 --> 01:43:54,996
I can have them
back in five minutes.

1175
01:43:56,671 --> 01:43:59,360
Al!
- How are ya?

1176
01:44:00,860 --> 01:44:04,031
Gee, you're looking great, fella.
See you're still with it.

1177
01:44:04,056 --> 01:44:06,829
Where you been? I dragged the
whole country for you. - Did you?

1178
01:44:08,270 --> 01:44:10,947
Oh, I... am I moved
around pretty much.

1179
01:44:12,276 --> 01:44:13,392
How is Sally?

1180
01:44:14,710 --> 01:44:18,610
Well, last I heard, she was in Florida.
Been through worst stuff, you know.

1181
01:44:18,917 --> 01:44:22,621
How's Carolyn? - Oh, I haven't
seen her since graduation.

1182
01:44:22,872 --> 01:44:26,231
She's up north somewhere. I keep
myself too busy to think about her.

1183
01:44:27,503 --> 01:44:30,521
Say, crew chief on a bomber,
that's doing all right in a year.

1184
01:44:30,546 --> 01:44:33,710
Oh, acting crew chief, sir.
You know, expansion.

1185
01:44:33,745 --> 01:44:35,503
Oh, don't give
me that "sir" stuff.

1186
01:44:35,538 --> 01:44:38,814
By rights, I should be taking
orders from you. - Young.  - Yes, sir.

1187
01:44:39,806 --> 01:44:41,650
Come meet your
commanding officer.

1188
01:44:49,605 --> 01:44:52,269
What's wrong with the emergency
release? - The door doesn't drop, sir.

1189
01:44:52,294 --> 01:44:56,196
Air Corps supply won't have
parts until tomorrow. - Well, Ludlow.

1190
01:44:56,442 --> 01:44:58,283
Can't stay away from it, can you?

1191
01:44:58,318 --> 01:45:01,244
Well, if I can't fly them, sir,
I can at least polish their wings.

1192
01:45:01,489 --> 01:45:04,184
I'm glad you're back
with us. - Thank you, sir.

1193
01:45:05,544 --> 01:45:07,200
I'll go get the report, sir.

1194
01:45:09,485 --> 01:45:12,927
It gets in your blood, doesn't it?
- There's a man who should be flying.

1195
01:45:13,194 --> 01:45:15,897
Hmm. - Can we
do something, sir?

1196
01:45:18,053 --> 01:45:20,381
And I've got a friend
or two in the chief's office.

1197
01:45:20,905 --> 01:45:22,936
Cases have been
reconsidered before.

1198
01:45:25,711 --> 01:45:27,664
Right now, we've
got other things to do.

1199
01:45:30,001 --> 01:45:32,501
She's all ready to go, sir,
except for that emergency release.

1200
01:45:32,533 --> 01:45:34,863
Well, we can't ground the ship for that.
Take care of it first thing tomorrow.

1201
01:45:34,888 --> 01:45:37,427
Yes, sir. Oh, sir.
This test is a new type

1202
01:45:37,452 --> 01:45:39,525
of experimental flare
on the way back tonight.

1203
01:45:39,549 --> 01:45:43,200
But don't install it in the bomb bay
until all the flares have been released.

1204
01:45:44,513 --> 01:45:47,498
Say, Al. I spoke to Mercer
about another crack at Kelly.

1205
01:45:47,522 --> 01:45:50,046
He said he'd go to bat for you.
- Do you think there's a chance?

1206
01:45:50,081 --> 01:45:52,030
You know Mercer.
If there's a chance, he'll swing it.

1207
01:45:52,065 --> 01:45:53,172
You really think so?
- Sure.

1208
01:45:53,173 --> 01:45:55,596
Look, right now,  I'm
racing to a pilot's meeting.

1209
01:45:55,631 --> 01:45:57,438
But when I get back tonight,
we have a lot to talk about.

1210
01:46:42,317 --> 01:46:44,028
Where can I find Lt. Young?

1211
01:46:46,902 --> 01:46:48,420
Al. - What are
you doing here?

1212
01:46:48,445 --> 01:46:51,774
They followed me here. The police
are out there now. - Get out of here!

1213
01:46:52,538 --> 01:46:55,156
But, Al. I'm your wife.
I'm in a jam. A bad one.

1214
01:46:55,181 --> 01:46:58,836
Tony Vanessa's dead. Somebody
killed him. They said I did it.

1215
01:46:58,861 --> 01:47:00,938
Did you?
- No.

1216
01:47:00,963 --> 01:47:04,432
Did you?
- Yes and I'd do it again.

1217
01:47:06,043 --> 01:47:09,064
You were born to kill
somebody, Sally. - Hit me.

1218
01:47:09,611 --> 01:47:12,669
Hurt me. - Shut up!
You can't stay here.

1219
01:47:12,943 --> 01:47:15,967
But I... You've always helped
me. You've never let me down.

1220
01:47:16,051 --> 01:47:17,196
You got any money?

1221
01:47:20,675 --> 01:47:22,026
Here. Take this.

1222
01:47:22,051 --> 01:47:24,966
When you see your chance, step out of
the hangar and get back to Los Angeles.

1223
01:47:25,001 --> 01:47:27,476
Will you meet me there, Al?
- You're on your own, Sally.

1224
01:47:27,511 --> 01:47:30,534
Al, please. I don't know where
to turn. I got to talk to somebody.

1225
01:47:30,559 --> 01:47:33,411
Please.
Tomorrow night, Al. Please.

1226
01:47:33,436 --> 01:47:35,162
All right. All right.

1227
01:47:35,762 --> 01:47:37,661
I'll meet you at the
bus station tomorrow night.

1228
01:47:39,142 --> 01:47:41,220
They must have turned
me out labeled "sucker".

1229
01:47:41,245 --> 01:47:43,495
Now get out of here.
We're taking off right away.

1230
01:47:43,530 --> 01:47:45,010
I'll see you
tomorrow night, Al.

1231
01:48:07,412 --> 01:48:08,849
Al, they're here.

1232
01:48:10,897 --> 01:48:11,983
Al!

1233
01:48:14,968 --> 01:48:15,968
Al!

1234
01:48:34,767 --> 01:48:37,462
Here we go again, boys.
- We're on our way.

1235
01:48:44,264 --> 01:48:47,393
The old man says we're going upstairs.
Here we go to play war games.

1236
01:48:47,465 --> 01:48:51,370
Yep. But it feels real this time.
- There's supposed to be an air raid tonight.

1237
01:49:07,717 --> 01:49:08,873
You all right?

1238
01:50:10,753 --> 01:50:13,433
Navigator to Commander.
Drift correction.

1239
01:50:13,458 --> 01:50:14,816
Two degrees left.

1240
01:50:14,841 --> 01:50:17,628
We're 45 seconds ahead
of our last checkpoint.

1241
01:50:22,615 --> 01:50:25,677
Put the manifold pressure
back to 23 inches.

1242
01:50:29,834 --> 01:50:32,748
Navigator to Commander.
Over Monterrey.

1243
01:50:33,441 --> 01:50:37,181
Anti-Aircraft Company.
Battery B. 52nd Monterrey.

1244
01:50:37,206 --> 01:50:40,940
Warning this command.
27 heavy bombers passing over here.

1245
01:50:40,965 --> 01:50:43,495
At estimated altitude 12.000.

1246
01:50:43,530 --> 01:50:45,408
Changing course from south to east.

1247
01:50:54,930 --> 01:50:57,860
Navigator to Commander.
Over Santa Barbara.

1248
01:50:57,885 --> 01:51:01,752
Directions to 32nd Squadron.
Extinguish your navigation light.

1249
01:51:05,455 --> 01:51:07,424
Hold your altitude at 12.000.

1250
01:51:33,461 --> 01:51:35,227
Navigator to Commander.

1251
01:51:35,696 --> 01:51:39,547
Estimate over Glendale.
One and 1/2 minutes.

1252
01:51:41,142 --> 01:51:43,463
Shows Los Angeles blacked out.

1253
01:51:46,752 --> 01:51:50,035
Bombardier to Commander.
Objective visible.

1254
01:51:51,624 --> 01:51:55,519
Mercer to 32nd Squadron.
Squadron approaching objective.

1255
01:51:55,544 --> 01:51:58,082
Bombardier, stand by to
release magnesium bombs.

1256
01:51:58,107 --> 01:51:59,558
And trail on assigned target.

1257
01:52:12,180 --> 01:52:15,601
Bombardier to Commander.
Opening bomb bay doors.

1258
01:52:44,901 --> 01:52:46,538
Directions to 32nd Squadron.

1259
01:52:46,563 --> 01:52:49,751
Formation 3000 feet above
preparing to attack on our left.

1260
01:52:49,776 --> 01:52:52,134
Squadron change formation.
To Javelin down.

1261
01:52:52,159 --> 01:52:54,407
All combat crew members,
maintain battle stations.

1262
01:52:55,813 --> 01:52:56,813
Here we go.

1263
01:53:30,060 --> 01:53:33,224
Mercer to 32nd Squadron.
Enter overcast.

1264
01:53:33,249 --> 01:53:36,796
Use regular ascent procedure.
Rendezvous on top of overcast.

1265
01:53:54,055 --> 01:53:56,133
Mercer to 32nd Squadron.

1266
01:53:56,158 --> 01:53:59,531
Proceed individually to simulated
occupation of dispersed airdrome.

1267
01:54:14,240 --> 01:54:16,068
Head for Muroc Dry Lake.

1268
01:54:34,072 --> 01:54:36,197
Simulate occupation
in about ten minutes.

1269
01:54:36,198 --> 01:54:39,535
Better get those experimental
flares installed. - Yes, sir.

1270
01:54:42,169 --> 01:54:45,128
Tentative results from GHQ, sir.

1271
01:54:50,134 --> 01:54:52,221
VS-1 to WMZ.

1272
01:54:52,475 --> 01:54:54,692
VS-1 to WMZ.

1273
01:54:55,243 --> 01:54:58,874
Commanding General First Wing.
GHQ Air Force, Marsh Field.

1274
01:54:59,424 --> 01:55:02,426
White Pursuit MP...
- Al.

1275
01:55:03,456 --> 01:55:06,213
Al, get me out of here.
I can't stand it here.

1276
01:55:06,238 --> 01:55:08,590
I can't breathe.
Let me go up front, Al.

1277
01:55:08,625 --> 01:55:10,793
Are you crazy? Do you
want them to see you?

1278
01:55:11,223 --> 01:55:14,083
Stay right here till I come and
get you. And stay put. - Al.

1279
01:55:14,108 --> 01:55:17,476
Look out for those flares. In fifteen
seconds, they  could blow us all to glory.

1280
01:55:17,500 --> 01:55:20,672
Understand? - Al, I can't stand
it in here any longer. I can't!

1281
01:55:20,673 --> 01:55:23,149
You will.
I'll knock you cold.

1282
01:55:23,174 --> 01:55:24,203
Al, don't leave me.

1283
01:55:27,695 --> 01:55:29,791
Al!
- Live flares!

1284
01:55:30,063 --> 01:55:33,135
Live flares!
- Live flares!

1285
01:55:33,311 --> 01:55:34,537
Live flares!

1286
01:55:36,084 --> 01:55:39,734
Open the bomb bay.
- Open the bomb bay doors.

1287
01:55:39,759 --> 01:55:41,695
Bombardier. Open the bomb bay doors.

1288
01:55:41,720 --> 01:55:43,914
Hit the emergency release
before it explodes.

1289
01:55:51,086 --> 01:55:53,101
Close this.
- What was that?

1290
01:55:54,039 --> 01:55:55,586
Where's the throw?

1291
01:56:16,210 --> 01:56:18,483
Straight.
We got it.

1292
01:56:18,548 --> 01:56:20,337
Keep going.
He caught it.

1293
01:56:20,968 --> 01:56:23,757
He caught it. - Get out that
chute. We're going down.

1294
01:56:23,782 --> 01:56:26,478
Are you crazy? That's against
all regulations. - We're going down.

1295
01:57:16,059 --> 01:57:18,770
Capt. Mercer.
Capt. Mercer.

1296
01:57:39,655 --> 01:57:41,843
He has serious burns, sir.
And head injuries.

1297
01:57:42,536 --> 01:57:44,234
Looks like internal injuries too.

1298
01:57:50,396 --> 01:57:53,470
I'm afraid he's dying.
Adrenaline, quick.

1299
01:57:56,041 --> 01:57:57,041
Yeah.

1300
01:57:59,024 --> 01:58:00,289
You're a fool.

1301
01:58:01,834 --> 01:58:03,035
Water.

1302
01:58:05,021 --> 01:58:08,389
Who taught you to land a plane
in the middle of the night in this spot?

1303
01:58:09,744 --> 01:58:11,851
Like this.
- Alcohol.

1304
01:58:13,167 --> 01:58:16,906
I didn't. - You're
pretty seriously hurt, sir.

1305
01:58:16,931 --> 01:58:18,556
We have to get
you to a hospital.

1306
01:58:19,368 --> 01:58:23,235
You're staying
right here? Jones.

1307
01:58:23,260 --> 01:58:24,423
Right here, sir.

1308
01:58:26,078 --> 01:58:28,843
Contact Marsh on
the main transmitter.

1309
01:58:30,496 --> 01:58:33,718
Tell them we're
staying here. - Yes, sir.

1310
01:58:33,743 --> 01:58:35,195
Never mind that message.

1311
01:58:36,516 --> 01:58:37,907
They'd okay it at Marsh.

1312
01:58:42,078 --> 01:58:45,924
We'll never get out
of here. That ridge.

1313
01:58:47,480 --> 01:58:51,253
We're taking off.
Anybody like to stay?

1314
01:58:54,913 --> 01:58:56,660
All right.
Get that stretcher.

1315
01:58:56,685 --> 01:58:57,685
Yes, sir.

1316
01:59:08,811 --> 01:59:11,452
Be careful.
- Easy now, fella.

1317
01:59:13,010 --> 01:59:15,051
All right. Set him down
here and get him covered up.

1318
01:59:15,853 --> 01:59:17,010
Check.

1319
01:59:59,726 --> 02:00:02,078
All right. Give me all
the manifold pressure she'll take.

1320
02:01:08,171 --> 02:01:10,163
Heads are frigid
on the one constrictor blade.

1321
02:01:12,373 --> 02:01:15,000
Drop that flap or
it tears the engine out.

1322
02:01:20,167 --> 02:01:22,152
She won't pull seven.
Line's busted.

1323
02:01:22,177 --> 02:01:23,277
Keep trying.

1324
02:01:28,069 --> 02:01:32,042
VS-1 to WMZ.
VS-1 to WMZ.

1325
02:01:32,481 --> 02:01:34,059
Ship's vibrating violently.

1326
02:01:35,135 --> 02:01:36,489
Well, our wings are still on.

1327
02:01:46,014 --> 02:01:48,967
Prepare for crash landing.
Prepare for crash landing.

1328
02:01:49,008 --> 02:01:51,905
Making crash landing.
Making crash landing.

1329
02:01:52,616 --> 02:01:54,077
All right, men. Get in here!

1330
02:01:58,039 --> 02:01:59,344
Try pumping it.

1331
02:02:09,696 --> 02:02:11,282
Pump it quickly.

1332
02:02:56,269 --> 02:02:57,370
Are you all right?

1333
02:03:06,606 --> 02:03:07,684
Sally.

1334
02:03:15,760 --> 02:03:16,807
Hold it.

1335
02:03:44,100 --> 02:03:46,194
Jeff.
Oh.

1336
02:03:47,772 --> 02:03:48,772
I say.

1337
02:03:51,539 --> 02:03:54,623
Make it go away, Al.

1338
02:03:58,555 --> 02:04:02,573
Thanks.
Thanks, Al.

1339
02:04:03,899 --> 02:04:06,511
This isn't hurting.
- No.

1340
02:04:10,112 --> 02:04:13,136
A really swell guy.

1341
02:04:13,161 --> 02:04:14,161
Oh.

1342
02:04:22,157 --> 02:04:23,223
Sally.

1343
02:04:28,381 --> 02:04:29,584
She got on the ship.

1344
02:04:31,694 --> 02:04:33,176
She was in trouble.

1345
02:04:47,154 --> 02:04:48,663
Yeah, I loved her.

1346
02:04:51,103 --> 02:04:52,400
I couldn't help it.

1347
02:04:58,685 --> 02:05:01,216
Lt. Young said the court
would never believe

1348
02:05:01,241 --> 02:05:04,126
that I didn't know my
wife was aboard the ship.

1349
02:05:04,326 --> 02:05:07,650
He said I'd be finished for good.
I never get another chance.

1350
02:05:08,725 --> 02:05:12,484
If he knew he had to go but. There
was no sense in both of us taking it.

1351
02:05:13,713 --> 02:05:16,884
That's why he pleaded
guilty. To shield me.

1352
02:05:17,755 --> 02:05:18,930
That's all.

1353
02:05:21,512 --> 02:05:24,612
No further witnesses.
- The room will be cleared.

1354
02:05:24,979 --> 02:05:27,057
While the court
deliberates its verdict.

1355
02:05:40,401 --> 02:05:43,073
Good luck.
- Why, Carolyn.

1356
02:05:43,760 --> 02:05:46,721
I heard about this and thought
you might want to see me.

1357
02:05:47,643 --> 02:05:51,356
Thanks for coming.
- I'm here to stay this time, Jeff.

1358
02:05:52,181 --> 02:05:55,090
If you want me.
- Yes, I want you.

1359
02:05:57,037 --> 02:06:00,646
But they're about to tie a tin
can to my tail. - It doesn't matter.

1360
02:06:01,185 --> 02:06:03,428
Maybe not to you.
But it will to a lot of people.

1361
02:06:04,225 --> 02:06:05,273
Darling.

1362
02:06:06,260 --> 02:06:08,664
A lot of people will never
know what you've done.

1363
02:06:09,040 --> 02:06:12,071
But I know.
I'm proud.

1364
02:06:12,096 --> 02:06:14,751
No matter what verdict
they reach in there.

1365
02:06:15,290 --> 02:06:16,431
I'm proud of you.

1366
02:06:26,658 --> 02:06:29,150
On the specification, charge one.

1367
02:06:30,757 --> 02:06:31,963
Not guilty.

1368
02:06:34,185 --> 02:06:37,357
The court finds that
Lt. Young's decision

1369
02:06:37,841 --> 02:06:41,341
to disregard Capt. Mercer's
command was justified.

1370
02:06:41,936 --> 02:06:43,872
Under the extraordinary circumstances.

1371
02:06:45,327 --> 02:06:47,296
Capt. Mercer's life was at stake.

1372
02:06:48,139 --> 02:06:50,108
And Lt. Young had
a reasonable right

1373
02:06:50,133 --> 02:06:52,804
to doubt the binding
nature of a command

1374
02:06:53,258 --> 02:06:55,539
given by a man so gravely injured.

1375
02:06:56,872 --> 02:06:59,232
On the specification, charge two.

1376
02:07:02,285 --> 02:07:03,414
Not guilty.

1377
02:07:20,986 --> 02:07:22,105
Goodbye, Jeff.

1378
02:07:23,276 --> 02:07:24,503
Good bye, sir.

1379
02:07:25,679 --> 02:07:26,679
Ludlow.

1380
02:07:27,525 --> 02:07:31,270
You made a monkey out of me
once at Kelly. - Don't do it again.

1381
02:07:31,494 --> 02:07:34,767
I won't, sir.
- Can I get a kiss?

1382
02:07:38,167 --> 02:07:40,650
You wanted wings,
mister? Go get them.

